<!--must be referenced from a third-party source-->\n| signature          = \n| signature_alt      = \n| signature_size     = \n| footnotes          = \n}}\n'''Victoria Rimell''' (1974) is a British [[classicist]] and Professor of Latin at the [[University of Warwick]]. Her research spans a wide range of [[Latin Literature|Roman authors]] and operates on the interface between [[classical philology]] and modern thought. Among her publications are books on [[Ovid]], [[Martial]] and [[Petronius]]. She serves on the council of the [[Society for the Promotion of Roman Studies]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.romansociety.org/about/governance/council-members.html|title=Council Members|website=romansociety.org|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nRimell studied Classics at [[King's College, Cambridge]] where she received a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] and an [[MPhil]] degree. She then moved to [[King's College, London]], graduating with a [[PhD]] in 2001. After working at [[University College, Oxford]], and [[Cambridge University]], she took up a position at [[Sapienza University of Rome]] in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lettere.uniroma1.it/users/victoria-rimell|title=Victoria Rimell|website=uniroma1.it|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref> Since 2016, she has worked at [[Warwick University]] as an Associate Professor and, from 2018, as a Professor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://warwick.ac.uk/fac/arts/classics/staff/rimell/|title=Professor Victoria Rimell|website=warwick.ac.uk|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Selected publications==\n*''Petronius and the Anatomy of Fiction'', Cambridge University Press, 2002\n* ''Ovid\u2019s Lovers: Desire, Difference, and the Poetic Imagination'', Cambridge University Press, 2006\n* ''Martial\u2019s Rome: Empire and the Ideology of Epigram'', Cambridge University Press, 2008\n* ''The Closure of Space in Roman Poetics: Empire\u2019s Inward Turn'', Cambridge University Press, 2015\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:British academics]]\n[[Category:British classical scholars]]\n[[Category:Women classical scholars]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's College London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n\n\n{{England-academic-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Infobox academic\n| honorific_prefix   = <!-- see [[MOS:CREDENTIAL]] and [[MOS:HONORIFIC]] -->\n| name               = Victoria Rimell\n| honorific_suffix   = \n| image              = \n| image_size         = \n| alt                = \n| caption            = \n| native_name        = \n| native_name_lang   = \n| birth_name         = <!-- use only if different from full/othernames -->\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1974|04|03}}\n| birth_place        = \n| death_date         = <!-- {{death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} (death date then birth date) -->\n| death_place        = \n| death_cause        = \n| region             = \n| nationality        = \n| citizenship        = \n| residence          = \n| other_names        = \n| occupation         = \n| period             = \n| known_for          = \n| home_town          = \n| title              = \n| boards             = <!--board or similar positions extraneous to main occupation-->\n| spouse             = \n| partner            = \n| children           = \n| parents            =\n| relatives          =\n| awards             = <!--notable national-level awards only-->\n| website            = \n| education          = [[King's College, Cambridge]] <br> [[King's College, London]]\n| alma_mater         = \n| thesis_title       = \n| thesis_url         = \n| thesis_year        = \n| school_tradition   = \n| doctoral_advisor   = \n| academic_advisors  = \n| influences         = <!--must be referenced from a third-party source-->\n| era                = \n| discipline         = [[Classics]]\n| sub_discipline     = [[Latin Literature]]\n| workplaces         = [[Roma La Sapienza]] <br> [[Warwick University]]\n| doctoral_students  = <!--only those with WP articles-->\n| notable_students   = <!--only those with WP articles-->\n| main_interests     = \n| notable_works      = \n| notable_ideas      = \n| influenced         = <!--must be referenced from a third-party source-->\n| signature          = \n| signature_alt      = \n| signature_size     = \n| footnotes          = \n}}\n'''Victoria Rimell''' (1974) is a British [[classicist]] and Professor of Latin at the [[University of Warwick]]. Her research spans a wide range of [[Latin Literature|Roman authors]] and operates on the interface between [[classical philology]] and modern thought. Among her publications are books on [[Ovid]], [[Martial]] and [[Petronius]]. She serves on the council of the [[Society for the Promotion of Roman Studies]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.romansociety.org/about/governance/council-members.html|title=Council Members|website=romansociety.org|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nRimell studied Classics at [[King's College, Cambridge]] where she received a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] and an [[MPhil]] degree. She then moved to [[King's College, London]], graduating with a [[PhD]] in 2001. After working at [[University College, Oxford]] and [[Cambridge University]], she took up a position at [[Sapienza University of Rome]] in 2004.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lettere.uniroma1.it/users/victoria-rimell|title=Victoria Rimell|website=uniroma1.it|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref> Since 2016, she has worked at [[Warwick University]] as an Associate Professor and, from 2018, as a Professor.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://warwick.ac.uk/fac/arts/classics/staff/rimell/|title=Professor Victoria Rimell|website=warwick.ac.uk|accessdate=9 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Selected Publications==\n*''Petronius and the Anatomy of Fiction'', Cambridge University Press, 2002\n* ''Ovid\u2019s Lovers: Desire, Difference, and the Poetic Imagination'', Cambridge University Press, 2006\n* ''Martial\u2019s Rome: Empire and the Ideology of Epigram'', Cambridge University Press, 2008\n* ''The Closure of Space in Roman Poetics: Empire\u2019s Inward Turn'', Cambridge University Press, 2015\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n[[Category:British academics]]\n[[Category:British classical scholars]]\n[[Category:Women classical scholars]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's College London]]\n[[Category:Alumni of King's College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:Alumni of the University of Cambridge]]\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n\n\n{{England-academic-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Chris the speller", "label": "safe", "comment": "replaced: Publications \u2192 publications,University College, Oxford\u2192University College, Oxford,", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Victoria_Rimell"}
{"title_page": "Hitchin", "text_new": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country           = England\n|coordinates       = {{coord|51.947|-0.283|display=inline,title}}\n|official_name     = Hitchin\n|static_image_name = St Mary's Church, Hitchin - geograph.org.uk - 989830.jpg\n|static_image_caption= View from Market Square in Hitchin, with [[St Mary's Church, Hitchin|St Mary's Church]] in the background\n|population        = 33,352\n|population_ref    =(2011)<ref name=\"census 2011\" >[http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadAreaSearch.do?a=7&r=1&i=1001&m=0&s=1364410010153&enc=1&areaSearchText=hitchin&areaSearchType=14&extendedList=true&searchAreas= Neighbourhood Statistics 2011 census combined  population of Hitchin wards], Accessed 27 March 2013</ref>\n|shire_district    = [[North Hertfordshire]]\n|shire_county      = [[Hertfordshire]]\n|region            = East of England\n|constituency_westminster= [[Hitchin and Harpenden (UK Parliament constituency)|Hitchin and Harpenden]]\n|post_town         = HITCHIN\n|postcode_district = SG4, SG5\n|postcode_area     = SG\n|dial_code         = 01462\n|os_grid_reference = TL181292\n}}\n[[File:St Marys Hitchin.JPG|thumb|[[St Mary's Church, Hitchin|St Mary's]], the Hitchin parish church]]\n'''Hitchin''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|h|\u026a|t\u0283|\u1d7b|n}}) is a [[market town]] in the [[North Hertfordshire]] [[Districts of England|district]] in [[Hertfordshire]], England, with an estimated population of 33,350.<ref name=\"census 2011\" />\n\n==History==\nHitchin is first noted as the central place of the Hicce people, a tribe holding 300 [[Hide (unit)|hides]] of land as mentioned in a 7th-century document,<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Gover, J E B, Mawer, A and Stenton, F M 1938 ''The Place-Names of Hertfordshire'' English Place-Names Society volume XV, 8</ref> the [[Tribal Hidage]]. Hicce, or Hicca may mean ''the people of the horse.''<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.north-herts.gov.uk/sites/northherts-cms/files/hiccaway-electronic-leaflet_0.pdf|title=North-Herts.gov.uk|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> The tribal name is [[Old English]] and derives from the [[Middle Angles|Middle Anglian]] people.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Anglo-Saxon England|last=Stenton|first=Sir Frank|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1971|isbn=0 19 821716 1|location=|pages=43, 296}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.historyfiles.co.uk/KingListsBritain/EnglandMiddleAngles.htm|title=History Files|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> It has been suggested that Hitchin was the location of '[[Councils of Clovesho|Clofeshoh]]', the place chosen in 673 by [[Theodore of Tarsus]] the [[Archbishop of Canterbury]] during the [[Synod of Hertford]], the first meeting of representatives of the fledgling [[Christianity|Christian]] churches of [[Anglo-Saxon England]], to hold annual synods of the churches as Theodore attempted to consolidate and centralise Christianity in England.<ref>{{Cite book|title=In search of Clofesho \u2013 the case for Hitchin|last=Offer|first=Clifford|date=2002|publisher=Tessa Publications|isbn=095421210X|location=Norwich|oclc=49552770}}</ref><ref>Hindley, ''The Anglo-Saxons - The beginnings of the English nation'', 47.</ref>\n\nBy 1086 Hitchin is described as a [[Royal Manor]] in [[Domesday Book]]: the feudal services of [[Avera and Inward]], usually found in the eastern counties, especially [[Cambridgeshire]] and [[Hertfordshire]],<ref name=\"ellis\">{{cite book | title=A general introduction to Domesday Book: accompanied by indexes of the tenants in chief, and under tenants, at the time of the survey, as wall as of the holders of lands ...  Volume 1 | author=Sir Henry Ellis | authorlink=Henry Ellis (librarian) | year=1833 | page=263 | publisher=Commission on the Public Records }}</ref> were due from the [[sokemen]],<ref name=\"vch\">{{cite book | chapter=Hitchin: Introduction and manors | title=A History of the County of Hertford | volume=3 | year=1912 | pages=3\u201312 | url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=43569 | accessdate=15 September 2010 }}</ref> but the manor of Hitchin was unique in levying Inward.<ref name=\"vch\" /> Evidence has been found to suggest that the town was once provided with an earthen bank and ditch fortification,<ref>Saunders, G & Winter, M 2009 ''Brooker's Yard, Hitchin, Hertfordshire: Archaeological Assessment Report'' The Heritage Network (report 560), 7</ref> probably in the early tenth century<ref>Fitzpatrick-Matthews, K J & Fitzpatrick-Matthews T 2008 ''The Archaeology of Hitchin from Prehistory to the Present'' North Hertfordshire District Council Museums & Hitchin Historical Society</ref> but this did not last. The modern spelling of the town first appears in 1618<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" /> in the ''\"Hertfordshire Feet of Fines\"''.\n\n[[File:Hitchin History - geograph.org.uk - 143243.jpg|thumb|Panel representing the foundational history of Hitchin mentioning: King Offa, the River Hiz and the Hicce tribe. Now on the front of Hitchin Library.]]\nThe name of the town also is associated with the small river that runs through it, most picturesquely in front of the east end of [[St. Mary's Church, Hitchin|St. Mary's Church]], the town's parish church. The river is noted on maps as the [[River Hiz]]. Contrary to how most people now pronounce the name, that is to say as spelt, the 'z' is an abbreviated character for a 'tch' sound in the Domesday Book<ref>Johnston, James B., The Place-Names of England and Wales, London, 1915, p. 305</ref> (as in the name of the town). It would have been pronounced 'River Hitch'. ''The Hicca Way'' is an eight-mile walking route along the River Hiz Valley, believed to have been used for trade between the Danes and English in the Anglo-Saxon age.<ref name=\"auto\" /> It is also likely that Hitch Wood, which lies some half a dozen miles south of the town also derives its name from the Hicce tribe, who gave their name to Hitchin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.prestonherts.co.uk/page148.html|title=Preston Herts|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n[[St. Mary's Church, Hitchin|St. Mary's Church]] is remarkably large for a town of its size and was once a Minster. The size of the church is evidence of how Hitchin prospered from the wool trade. It is the largest parish church in [[Hertfordshire]].<ref>{{Cite book|title = Hitchin Through Time|last = Madgin|first = Hugh|publisher = Amberley Publishing|year = 2009|isbn = 1848687451|location = Britain & Ireland|pages = }}</ref> Most of the church dates from the 15th century, with its tower dating from around 1190. During the laying of a new floor in the church in 1911, foundations of a more ancient church building were found. In form, they appear to be a [[basilica]]n church of a 7th-century type, with a later enlarged [[chancel]] and [[transept]]s, perhaps added in the 10th century. This makes the church older than the story (not recorded before the 15th century) that the church was founded by [[Offa]], king of [[Mercia]] 757-796.\n\nIn 1697, Hitchin (and the nearby village of [[Offley]]) were subject to what is thought to have been the most severe [[hail]]storm in recorded British history. Hailstones over 4&nbsp;inches in diameter were reported<ref>Tailor, Robert (May 1697), \"Account of a Great Hailstorm\", ''Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society (Great Britain)''; vol. 19, pp. 577-578</ref>\n\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Bucks Head sign.png|thumb|The Buck's Head pub sign, depicting Henry VIII's supposed escapade in Hitchin]] -->\nThe town flourished on the wool trade, and located near the [[Icknield Way]] and by the 17th century Hitchin was a staging post for coaches coming from [[London]]. By the middle of the 19th century the railway had arrived, and with it a new way of life for Hitchin. The [[corn exchange]] was built in the [[market place]] and within a short time Hitchin established itself as a major centre for grain trading.\n\nThe latter half of the 20th century has also brought great changes in communication to Hitchin. Motorways have shortened the journey time and brought [[Luton]], a few miles away on the [[M1 motorway|M1]], and the [[A1 road (Great Britain)|A1 (M)]] even closer. By the close of the 20th century, Hitchin had developed a strong commuter interest being midway between London and Cambridge. Hitchin also developed a fairly strong [[Sikh]] community based around the [[Walsworth]] area.\n\nDuring the medieval period, both a priory (Newbigging, now known as The Biggin) and a friary (now known as [[Hitchin Priory]]) were established, both of which closed during [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]]'s [[Dissolution of the Monasteries]]. They were never reformed, although The Biggin was for many years used as [[almshouse]]s.\n\nThe [[British Schools Museum]] in Hitchin is home to the world's only surviving complete [[Lancasterian Schoolroom]], which was built in 1837 to teach boys by the [[Lancasterian method]] ([[peer tutoring]]). This unique community project demonstrates the foundation of education for all.\n\nGirton College \u2013 a pioneer in women's education \u2013 was established on 16 October 1869 under the name of College for Women at Benslow House in Hitchin, which was considered to be a convenient distance from Cambridge and London. It was thought to be less 'risky' and less controversial to locate the college away from Cambridge in the beginning. The college moved to Cambridge a few years later and adopted its present name, [[Girton College]].\n\n==Government==\nHitchin is in the [[Non-metropolitan district|local government district]] of [[North Hertfordshire]] which was formed in 1974 by the amalgamation of rural and urban councils. There is now no town council in Hitchin.<ref>{{cite web|title=Councils and Politics|url=http://www.hitchinforum.org.uk/about-hitchin/council-mp/|publisher=Hitchin Forum|accessdate=25 February 2012}}</ref> Residents elect 13 members to the [[North Hertfordshire District Council]]. There are five electoral wards in Hitchin: [[Bearton]], [[Highbury Ward|Highbury]], [[Hitchin Oughton|Oughton]], Priory and [[Walsworth]].\n\nThe town is represented in [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] by the constituency of [[Hitchin and Harpenden (UK Parliament constituency)|Hitchin and Harpenden]]. The incumbent [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] MP [[Bim Afolami]] was [[2017 United Kingdom general election|elected in 2017]]. Between 1983 and 1997 Hitchin was included in the constituency of [[North Hertfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North Hertfordshire]]. Before that it was in the constituency of [[Hitchin (UK Parliament constituency)|Hitchin]].\n\nIn the [[European Parliament]], Hitchin was represented by the [[East of England (European Parliament constituency)|East of England]] constituency, which elected 7 [[Member of the European Parliament|MEPs]]. Prior to 1999 and the adoption of [[proportional representation]], it was in the European constituency of [[Hertfordshire (European Parliament constituency)|Hertfordshire]].\n\n==Transport==\n\n=== Rail ===\n{{See also|Hitchin railway station}}\n[[Hitchin railway station]] is on the [[East Coast Main Line|Great Northern Line]], and is also on the [[Cambridge Line]] as the last stop before it diverges towards Cambridge, {{Convert|1.42|km|mi|abbr=}} to the north east of the Hitchin. The station is a call on services provided by [[Govia Thameslink Railway]] under its Great Northern and Thameslink brands. These provide direct connections to [[Cambridge railway station|Cambridge]], [[Letchworth Garden City railway station|Letchworth Garden City]], [[London King's Cross railway station|London Kings Cross]] and [[St Pancras railway station|St Pancras International]], [[Peterborough railway station|Peterborough]], [[Gatwick Airport railway station|Gatwick Airport]], [[Three Bridges railway station|Three Bridges]] and [[Brighton railway station|Brighton]]. Journeys to London and Cambridge typically take 33 minutes. Journeys to Stevenage is take 5 minutes, Peterborough 45 minutes, and Gatwick Airport 78 minutes.\n\nHitchin Rail Users Group serve as the local voluntary group actively consulting with train companies on behalf of local people.\n\n=== Road ===\nThe [[A505 road|A505]], A600 and [[A602 road|A602]] roads intersect in Hitchin, which is about {{convert|3|mi|km|0|spell=in}} from the [[A1(M) motorway]] and about {{convert|10|mi|km|0|spell=in}} from the [[M1 motorway]].\n\n=== Aviation ===\nHitchin is about {{Convert|14.48|km|mi|abbr=}} from Luton Airport, with a direct bus service linking the two. The connections are provided by the 39 minutes by National Express (number 787) or 46 minutes by Arriva in Herts and Essex (''100 Saphire'' services).\n\n==Education==\n{{see also|List of schools in Hertfordshire|Hertfordshire#Education}}\nThere are several primary schools in Hitchin. Secondary education is provided at [[Hitchin Girls' School]], [[Hitchin Boys' School]] and the [[The Priory School, Hitchin|Priory School]]. There is a campus of the [[North Hertfordshire College]] in Hitchin, and it is also the home of the [[Benslow Music Trust]] which provides music education for adults, while North Herts Music School adjoined to Hitchin Girls' School delivers music lessons & activities for children & young people.\n\n[https://northhertsmuseum.org/ North Hertfordshire Museum] has an extensive collection that tells the story of the town and wider area from prehistoric times. The [[British Schools Museum]] is housed in original Edwardian and Victorian school buildings.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-48693086|title=New museum finally opens after six-year argument|date=2019-07-06|access-date=2019-10-27|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Culture and community==\n[[File:Queen Mother Theatre Hitchin.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Queen Mother Theatre]] in the town]]\n[[File:Hitchin lavender fields.jpg|thumb|right|Lavender fields near Hitchin]]\nIn March 2013 a poll in ''[[The Times]]'' voted Hitchin the 9th best town in the UK in which to live.<ref>{{cite web|last=Burge|first=Laura|title=Hitchin Voted 9th Best Town In UK|url=http://www.thecomet.net/news/hitchin_voted_as_ninth_best_town_in_uk_1_1985557|work=The Comet 24|publisher=Archant Community Media Ltd|accessdate=20 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nHitchin hosts an annual Arts and Music Festival with over 100 events taking place during the month. Hitchin Festival includes picnics, concerts, theatre, ghost walks, art exhibitions, comedy club, talks, summer fetes and fireworks.<ref>{{cite web|last=Burge|first=Laura|title=Hitchin Festival to launch|url=http://www.thecomet.net/news/hitchin_festival_to_launch_1_947747|work=The Comet 24|publisher=Archant Community Media Ltd|accessdate=25 February 2012}}</ref> Since 2014, Hitchin has hosted the yarn festival, organised and run by members of Hitchin Stitchin.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nMusic plays a very big part all year round with many venues hosting regular gigs. Hitchin Folk Club is one of the longest running and most respected clubs in the country meeting at The Sun Hotel on Sunday evenings; Hitchin Light Orchestra, Hitchin Symphony Orchestra and Hitchin Chamber Orchestra give regular concerts often in St Mary's Church and Hitchin Band perform around the country in brass band championship competition as well as the home town.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecomet.net/news/band-return-to-top-level-competition-1-5936320|title=Hitchin brass band to play at top level competition for first time in 33 years|last=Mountney|first=Dan|website=The Comet|language=en|access-date=2019-10-27}}</ref>\n\nAn independent music venue, Club 85, hosts an \"eclectic mix of contemporary bands and DJs\" in the area.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/going-places-hitchin-0rswrzbdz|title=Going Places: Hitchin|last=Maslen|first=Cherry|date=2017-09-24|work=The Sunday Times|access-date=2019-10-27|language=en|issn=0956-1382}}</ref>\n\nThere are two small theatres in the town. [[The Market Theatre, Hitchin|The Market Theatre]], a professional theatre, has a year-round programme including comedy plays, thrillers, historical shows, jazz nights and cocktail evenings. The Market Theatre is known for its annual Adult Panto (running between December and May) which also tours nationally. Additionally, the [[Queen Mother Theatre]] hosts the town's Bancroft Players, Big Spirit Youth Theatre and occasional visiting companies as well as Hitchin Films in the Richard Whitmore Studio.\n\nHitchin Market remains one of the largest in the area with general markets every Tuesday and Saturday, a bric-a-brac and collectables market on Fridays, and a Sunday Car Boot. There are also Local Produce and Crafts specialist markets on the last Saturday of each month. A Lifestyle market is held on every second Saturday of the month, while infrequently there are occasional Art Markets. Hitchin Markets is also the venue for the annual Duck Race during Hitchin Festival.\n\nThe town centre has a wealth of independent retailers in food and drink and fashion and the historic core is a place to find niche boutiques. Since 1995, Hitchin has benefitted from award-winning town centre management and in 2009 established one of Hertfordshire's first Business Improvement Districts.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2019 the town's centre was a finalist for England in the [[Visa Inc.|Visa]]/[[Government of the United Kingdom|UK Government]] Great British High Street Awards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecomet.net/news/hitchin-features-in-great-british-high-street-awards-2019-1-6211386|title=Hitchin's town centre nominated for national high street award|last=Thorburn|first=Jacob|website=The Comet|language=en|access-date=2019-10-27}}</ref>\n\nThere are a number of organisations for young people, including [[Air Training Corps|1066 Hitchin Squadron ATC]], [[Army Cadet Force|Hitchin Army Cadets]], [[Sea Cadet Corps|Sea Cadets Letchworth and Hitchin]], as well as various [[scouting]] groups.\n\nThe main burial ground for the town is [[Hitchin Cemetery]] on St. John's Road.\n\nHitchin is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n* [[File:Flag of France.svg|25px]] [[Nuits-St-Georges]], [[France]]\n* [[File:Flag of Germany.svg|25px]] [[Bingen am Rhein]], [[Germany]]\n\n==Sport in Hitchin==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=December 2017}}\n[[File:Top Field - Hitchin Town FC 02.jpg|thumb|[[Top Field]], the home ground of [[Hitchin Town F.C.]]]]\n\n=== Rugby Union ===\n{{See also|Hitchin Rugby Club}}\n[[Hitchin Rugby Club]] was founded in 1954 and competes in [[rugby union]] at all age levels within the Hitchin area. This includes teams at ages 7 to 12, 13 to 17, under 19s, seniors, over 35s, and a Ladies side.\n\nThe club's highlights have included playing at [[Twickenham]] in the final of the national Junior RFU Cup in 1993 and the establishment of the country's first Academy. Currently membership stands at over 500 people. The club are also active as a voluntary group with their community development programme.\n\n=== Association Football ===\n{{See also|Hitchin Town F.C.}}\n[[Hitchin Town F.C.]] was established in 1865 and later reformed in 1928. It is one of only three clubs who competed in the inaugural [[FA Cup]], paying the then \u00a325 entry fee (\u00a32,892 in 2019 adjusted for inflation),<ref name=\":1\">{{Citation|title=Half time rants & last minute equalisers {{!}} Experiencing a match day with Hitchin Town|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Wysl5ye3TF0|language=en|access-date=2019-10-27}}</ref> and continue to compete. They claim to be the second oldest club in English football, but some dispute this due to the reformation in the 1920s.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe side currently compete in the [[Southern Football League|Southern League Premier Division Central]], the seventh tier of English football. The club play at 4,554-capacity ground Top Field, in the north of the town, and came close to achieving promotion in the late 2010s, but have recently come into a more troubled spell.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nTheir highlights include wins in the F.A. Cup against higher ranked sides Hereford United in 1994 and Bristol Rovers in 1995 during which period they developed a reputation for \"giant-killing\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45863255|title=FA Cup fourth qualifying round: Cup heroes revisited, Houdini acts and a Barnet bus bonanza|date=2018-10-18|access-date=2019-10-27|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nThe side count Hitchin-born England international [[Jack Wilshere]] among their supporters. Wilshire studied at the Priory School in the town and now runs a youth scheme called the Jack Wilshere Soccer School.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecomet.net/sport/football/exclusive-humble-jack-wilshere-backs-mark-burke-s-battling-hitchin-town-as-fa-cup-date-looms-with-bbc-set-to-broadcast-first-round-draw-from-top-field-if-canaries-progress-1-5743469|title=EXCLUSIVE: Humble Jack Wilshere backs Mark Burke's battling Hitchin Town as FA Cup date looms - with BBC set to broadcast first round draw from Top Field if Canaries progress|last=YOUSIF|first=EXCLUSIVE BY LAYTH|website=The Comet|language=en|access-date=2019-10-27}}</ref>\n\nThe club were featured by [[Sky Sports]] during their coverage of [[Non-League Day]] 2019 (taking place on 12 October each year), with the broadcaster following the match day experience at the club.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Other sports ===\nHitchin is also home to Blueharts Hockey Club, a leading club since 1946, with 7 men's teams and 7 women's team plus a thriving junior section.\n\nIt also houses [[Hitchin Cricket Club]], which has been an important cricket club within the area since 1866.\n\nHitchin Swimming Club are based locally and competes at local, county and regional level.\n\nThe Hitchin Nomads Cycling Club, which caters for many competitive and non-competitive cycling disciplines, was formed in the town in 1931. It is affiliated to British Cycling, the Cyclists' Touring Club, Cycling time trials and local cycling associations. Notable former members include pre-eminent cycling [[travel writer]] [[Harold Briercliffe]] and Max Pendleton, father of [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] gold-medallist and [[Cycling World Championship|track cycling World Champion]] [[Victoria Pendleton]].\n\nFormed in 2003 and known as FVS TRI until November 2009, Team Trisports is a Hitchin-based triathlon club. In addition to triathlon, the club an England Athletics and British Cycling affiliate.\n\nHitchin Running Club was formed in 2008 and is one of the most popular clubs in the town. They enjoy a large fan base and many local people of all abilities take part in the social activities. They are based at the rugby club and are a not for profit organisation.\n\n==Districts of Hitchin==\n* [[Bearton]]\n* [[Benslow]]\n* [[Poets Estate (Hitchin)|Poets Estate]]\n* [[Purwell]]\n* [[Sunnyside (Hitchin)|Sunnyside]]\n* [[Walsworth]]\n* [[West Hitchin]]\n* [[Westmill (Hitchin)|Westmill]]\n\n==Nearby settlements==\n[[Ickleford]] is a village situated on the northern outskirts of Hitchin, and to the south is [[St Ippolyts]], [[Charlton, Hertfordshire|Charlton]] and [[Gosmore]]. The nearest towns are [[Letchworth]], [[Baldock]], [[Stevenage]] and [[Luton]].\n\n==Notable people who have lived in Hitchin==\n{{more citations needed section|date=January 2017}}\n{{See also|Category:People from Hitchin}}\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|* [[BadBoyYardie]], gangster rapper, producer, businessman, entrepreneur\n* [[Dorothy Atkinson]], actress\n* [[Guillem Balagu\u00e9]], Spanish football journalist\n* [[James Bay (singer)|James Bay]], musician\n* [[Tom Bentley]], philanthropist\n* [[Henry Bessemer]], engineer\n* [[Jennie Bond]], journalist\n* [[Sally Bretton]], actress\n* [[Harold Briercliffe]], cyclist and author\n* [[Drewe Broughton]], footballer\n* [[Edward Chapman (publisher)|Edward Chapman]], publisher\n* [[George Chapman]], poet\n* [[Oliver Cheshire]], fashion model\n* [[Chris Cleaver]], footballer\n* [[Bill Coleman (cricketer)|Bill Coleman]], cricketer\n* [[Mary Angela Dickens]], novelist and granddaughter of [[Charles Dickens]]\n* [[Monica Dickens]], novelist and great granddaughter of [[Charles Dickens]]\n* [[Karl Duguid]], footballer\n* [[Willie Duncan]], musician\n* [[Gail Emms]], badminton player\n* [[Ross Flitney]], footballer\n* [[Mathew Gates]], figure skater\n* [[Martin Gordon]], musician\n* [[F.L. Griggs]], etcher\n* [[Henry Hawkins, 1st Baron Brampton]], judge\n* [[E O Higgins]], author\n* [[Reginald Hine]], solicitor and historian\n* [[Paul Jesson]], actor\n* [[Roy Kettle]], author\n* [[Thea King]], clarinettist\n* [[Dave Kitson]], footballer\n* [[Kane Kramer]], inventor of the digital audio player\n* [[Frank Launder]], film director\n* [[Joseph Lister, 1st Baron Lister|Joseph Lister]], pioneer of antiseptic surgery\n* [[John Lloyd (graphic designer)|John Lloyd]], co-founder of the international design consultancy Lloyd Northover.\n* [[Gavin McInnes]], writer, political commentator \n* [[Sally Biddulph|Sally Mules]], journalist and presenter\n* [[Elaine Murray]], Scottish politician\n* Dixie Newberry, National darts champion 1949-1950\n* [[Robert Newman (comedian)|Robert Newman]], comedian\n* [[David Noble (footballer, born 1982)|David Noble]], footballer\n* [[Arvind Parmar]], tennis player\n* [[Ian Perkins]], Musician\n* [[Kevin Phillips (footballer)|Kevin Phillips]], footballer\n* [[Richard Shannon]], chief of advertising and tourism in Lloret de Mar\n* [[Kevin Pilkington]], footballer\n* [[Ian Poulter]], golfer\n* [[Pam Rhodes]], [[BBC]] TV presenter<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thespeakersagency.com/speaker/pam-rhodes/ |title=Pam Rhodes |work=The Speakers Agency |accessdate=10 September 2017 }}</ref>\n* [[Helen Richardson-Walsh]], England and Great Britain hockey player. Multiple Olympic medalist, EuroHockey Nations champion and Champions challenge winner. \n* [[Michael Robbins]], actor\n* [[Robert Tor Russell]], architect of [[New Delhi]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxfordartonline.com/subscriber/article/grove/art/T074580?q=Robert+Tor+Russell&search=quick&pos=1&_start=1#firsthit |title=Russell, Robert Tor in Oxford Art Online |publisher=www.oxfordartonline.com |accessdate=6 September 2010 }} (requires login or UK library card)</ref>\n* [[Martin Savage (actor)|Martin Savage]], actor\n* [[Steve Sheppard]],  B.B.C. Cricket and football commentator and owner of One World Music\n* [[Valerie Singleton]], TV presenter\n* [[Richard Walker (angler)|Richard Walker]], angler\n* [[Diana Wallis]], politician (MEP)\n* [[Kristiina Wheeler]], an English-Finnish singer\n* [[Richard Whitmore]], former newsreader\n* Sir [[Frank Whittle]], inventor of the jet engine\n* [[Jack Wilshere]], footballer\n* [[Henry Wood (conductor)|Henry Wood]], conductor\n* Second Lieutenant [[Frank Edward Young (VC)|Frank Young VC]], recipient of the [[Victoria Cross]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bedfordregiment.org.uk/Hertsrgt/youngvc.html|title=Second Lieutenant Frank Edward Young VC|publisher=www.bedfordregiment.org.uk|accessdate=2 June 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Gary Younge]], journalist\n* [[The Bleach Boys]], Punk Band dating from 1976}}\n\n==Filmography==\nMike Leigh\u2019s 1982 film \u2018\u2019[[Home Sweet Home (1982 film)|Home Sweet Home]]\u2019\u2019 for BBC Television was set in Hitchin. [[File:Hitchin Market Square 2018.jpg|thumb|right|Various scenes in ''[[Doctor Foster (TV series)|Doctor Foster]]'' were filmed at the Market Square in Hitchin]]\nPart of the 2010 BBC TV series ''[[Just William (2010 TV serial)|Just William]]'' was filmed at the [[British Schools Museum]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Judge|first=Ann|title=The BBC 'Just William' at Hitchin British Schools|url=http://www.hertsmemories.org.uk/page_id__2258_path__0p34p109p.aspx|work=Herts Memories|publisher=[[Hertfordshire County Council]]|accessdate=25 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nScenes from the BBC drama series ''[[Doctor Foster (TV series)|Doctor Foster]]'' were filmed in Hitchin, as well as the Channel 4 series ''[[Humans (TV series)|Humans]]''.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\n==Miscellaneous==\nIn 1960 Hitchin [[Urban District Council]] was the first in Britain to introduce 'black bags' for refuse collection.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\n[[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|Elizabeth the Queen Mother]]'s birth in 1900 was registered at Hitchin, which is a few miles from her parent's [[English country house]], [[St Paul's Walden Bury]], where she spent much of her childhood.\n\nThe 1951 book ''[[My Turn to Make the Tea]]'' by [[Monica Dickens]] is set in Hitchin (renamed Downingham in the book).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Hitchin}}\n{{wikivoyage|Hitchin}}\n* [http://www.hitchinhistoricals.org.uk/ Hitchin Historical Society]\n* [http://www.hitchinsociety.org.uk/ Hitchin Society]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170709150242/http://www.alehouses.info/hitchin/ Historical Map of Hitchin Pubs], an interactive map of Hitchin public houses both current and closed.\n* {{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Hitchin|short=x}}\n\n{{Hertfordshire}}\n{{Civil parishes of Hertfordshire}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hitchin| ]]\n[[Category:Towns in Hertfordshire]]\n[[Category:Market towns in Hertfordshire]]\n[[Category:Unparished areas in Hertfordshire]]\n[[Category:North Hertfordshire District]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other uses}}\n{{Infobox UK place\n|country           = England\n|coordinates       = {{coord|51.947|-0.283|display=inline,title}}\n|official_name     = Hitchin\n|static_image_name = St Mary's Church, Hitchin - geograph.org.uk - 989830.jpg\n|static_image_caption= View from Market Square in Hitchin, with [[St Mary's Church, Hitchin|St Mary's Church]] in the background\n|population        = 33,352\n|population_ref    =(2011)<ref name=\"census 2011\" >[http://www.neighbourhood.statistics.gov.uk/dissemination/LeadAreaSearch.do?a=7&r=1&i=1001&m=0&s=1364410010153&enc=1&areaSearchText=hitchin&areaSearchType=14&extendedList=true&searchAreas= Neighbourhood Statistics 2011 census combined  population of Hitchin wards], Accessed 27 March 2013</ref>\n|shire_district    = [[North Hertfordshire]]\n|shire_county      = [[Hertfordshire]]\n|region            = East of England\n|constituency_westminster= [[Hitchin and Harpenden (UK Parliament constituency)|Hitchin and Harpenden]]\n|post_town         = HITCHIN\n|postcode_district = SG4, SG5\n|postcode_area     = SG\n|dial_code         = 01462\n|os_grid_reference = TL181292\n}}\n[[File:St Marys Hitchin.JPG|thumb|[[St Mary's Church, Hitchin|St Mary's]], the Hitchin parish church]]\n'''Hitchin''' ({{IPAc-en|\u02c8|h|\u026a|t\u0283|\u1d7b|n}}) is a [[market town]] in the [[North Hertfordshire]] [[Districts of England|district]] in [[Hertfordshire]], England, with an estimated population of 33,350.<ref name=\"census 2011\" />\n\n==History==\nHitchin is first noted as the central place of the Hicce people, a tribe holding 300 [[Hide (unit)|hides]] of land as mentioned in a 7th-century document,<ref name=\"ReferenceA\">Gover, J E B, Mawer, A and Stenton, F M 1938 ''The Place-Names of Hertfordshire'' English Place-Names Society volume XV, 8</ref> the [[Tribal Hidage]]. Hicce, or Hicca may mean ''the people of the horse.''<ref name=\"auto\">{{Cite web|url=http://www.north-herts.gov.uk/sites/northherts-cms/files/hiccaway-electronic-leaflet_0.pdf|title=North-Herts.gov.uk|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> The tribal name is [[Old English]] and derives from the [[Middle Angles|Middle Anglian]] people.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Anglo-Saxon England|last=Stenton|first=Sir Frank|publisher=Oxford University Press|year=1971|isbn=0 19 821716 1|location=|pages=43, 296}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.historyfiles.co.uk/KingListsBritain/EnglandMiddleAngles.htm|title=History Files|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref> It has been suggested that Hitchin was the location of '[[Councils of Clovesho|Clofeshoh]]', the place chosen in 673 by [[Theodore of Tarsus]] the [[Archbishop of Canterbury]] during the [[Synod of Hertford]], the first meeting of representatives of the fledgling [[Christianity|Christian]] churches of [[Anglo-Saxon England]], to hold annual synods of the churches as Theodore attempted to consolidate and centralise Christianity in England.<ref>{{Cite book|title=In search of Clofesho \u2013 the case for Hitchin|last=Offer|first=Clifford|date=2002|publisher=Tessa Publications|isbn=095421210X|location=Norwich|oclc=49552770}}</ref><ref>Hindley, ''The Anglo-Saxons - The beginnings of the English nation'', 47.</ref>\n\nBy 1086 Hitchin is described as a [[Royal Manor]] in [[Domesday Book]]: the feudal services of [[Avera and Inward]], usually found in the eastern counties, especially [[Cambridgeshire]] and [[Hertfordshire]],<ref name=\"ellis\">{{cite book | title=A general introduction to Domesday Book: accompanied by indexes of the tenants in chief, and under tenants, at the time of the survey, as wall as of the holders of lands ...  Volume 1 | author=Sir Henry Ellis | authorlink=Henry Ellis (librarian) | year=1833 | page=263 | publisher=Commission on the Public Records }}</ref> were due from the [[sokemen]],<ref name=\"vch\">{{cite book | chapter=Hitchin: Introduction and manors | title=A History of the County of Hertford | volume=3 | year=1912 | pages=3\u201312 | url=http://www.british-history.ac.uk/report.aspx?compid=43569 | accessdate=15 September 2010 }}</ref> but the manor of Hitchin was unique in levying Inward.<ref name=\"vch\" /> Evidence has been found to suggest that the town was once provided with an earthen bank and ditch fortification,<ref>Saunders, G & Winter, M 2009 ''Brooker's Yard, Hitchin, Hertfordshire: Archaeological Assessment Report'' The Heritage Network (report 560), 7</ref> probably in the early tenth century<ref>Fitzpatrick-Matthews, K J & Fitzpatrick-Matthews T 2008 ''The Archaeology of Hitchin from Prehistory to the Present'' North Hertfordshire District Council Museums & Hitchin Historical Society</ref> but this did not last. The modern spelling of the town first appears in 1618<ref name=\"ReferenceA\" /> in the ''\"Hertfordshire Feet of Fines\"''.\n\n[[File:Hitchin History - geograph.org.uk - 143243.jpg|thumb|Panel representing the foundational history of Hitchin mentioning: King Offa, the River Hiz and the Hicce tribe. Now on the front of Hitchin Library.]]\nThe name of the town also is associated with the small river that runs through it, most picturesquely in front of the east end of [[St. Mary's Church, Hitchin|St. Mary's Church]], the town's parish church. The river is noted on maps as the [[River Hiz]]. Contrary to how most people now pronounce the name, that is to say as spelt, the 'z' is an abbreviated character for a 'tch' sound in the Domesday Book<ref>Johnston, James B., The Place-Names of England and Wales, London, 1915, p. 305</ref> (as in the name of the town). It would have been pronounced 'River Hitch'. ''The Hicca Way'' is an eight-mile walking route along the River Hiz Valley, believed to have been used for trade between the Danes and English in the Anglo-Saxon age.<ref name=\"auto\" /> It is also likely that Hitch Wood, which lies some half a dozen miles south of the town also derives its name from the Hicce tribe, who gave their name to Hitchin.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.prestonherts.co.uk/page148.html|title=Preston Herts|last=|first=|date=|website=|access-date=}}</ref>\n\n[[St. Mary's Church, Hitchin|St. Mary's Church]] is remarkably large for a town of its size and was once a Minster. The size of the church is evidence of how Hitchin prospered from the wool trade. It is the largest parish church in [[Hertfordshire]].<ref>{{Cite book|title = Hitchin Through Time|last = Madgin|first = Hugh|publisher = Amberley Publishing|year = 2009|isbn = 1848687451|location = Britain & Ireland|pages = }}</ref> Most of the church dates from the 15th century, with its tower dating from around 1190. During the laying of a new floor in the church in 1911, foundations of a more ancient church building were found. In form, they appear to be a [[basilica]]n church of a 7th-century type, with a later enlarged [[chancel]] and [[transept]]s, perhaps added in the 10th century. This makes the church older than the story (not recorded before the 15th century) that the church was founded by [[Offa]], king of [[Mercia]] 757-796.\n\nIn 1697, Hitchin (and the nearby village of [[Offley]]) were subject to what is thought to have been the most severe [[hail]]storm in recorded British history. Hailstones over 4&nbsp;inches in diameter were reported<ref>Tailor, Robert (May 1697), \"Account of a Great Hailstorm\", ''Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society (Great Britain)''; vol. 19, pp. 577-578</ref>\n\n<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Bucks Head sign.png|thumb|The Buck's Head pub sign, depicting Henry VIII's supposed escapade in Hitchin]] -->\nThe town flourished on the wool trade, and located near the [[Icknield Way]] and by the 17th century Hitchin was a staging post for coaches coming from [[London]]. By the middle of the 19th century the railway had arrived, and with it a new way of life for Hitchin. The [[corn exchange]] was built in the [[market place]] and within a short time Hitchin established itself as a major centre for grain trading.\n\nThe latter half of the 20th century has also brought great changes in communication to Hitchin. Motorways have shortened the journey time and brought [[Luton]], a few miles away on the [[M1 motorway|M1]], and the [[A1 road (Great Britain)|A1 (M)]] even closer. By the close of the 20th century, Hitchin had developed a strong commuter interest being midway between London and Cambridge. Hitchin also developed a fairly strong [[Sikh]] community based around the [[Walsworth]] area.\n\nDuring the medieval period, both a priory (Newbigging, now known as The Biggin) and a friary (now known as [[Hitchin Priory]]) were established, both of which closed during [[Henry VIII of England|Henry VIII]]'s [[Dissolution of the Monasteries]]. They were never reformed, although The Biggin was for many years used as [[almshouse]]s.\n\nThe [[British Schools Museum]] in Hitchin is home to the world's only surviving complete [[Lancasterian Schoolroom]], which was built in 1837 to teach boys by the [[Lancasterian method]] ([[peer tutoring]]). This unique community project demonstrates the foundation of education for all.\n\nGirton College \u2013 a pioneer in women's education \u2013 was established on 16 October 1869 under the name of College for Women at Benslow House in Hitchin, which was considered to be a convenient distance from Cambridge and London. It was thought to be less 'risky' and less controversial to locate the college away from Cambridge in the beginning. The college moved to Cambridge a few years later and adopted its present name, [[Girton College]].\n\n==Government==\nHitchin is in the [[Non-metropolitan district|local government district]] of [[North Hertfordshire]] which was formed in 1974 by the amalgamation of rural and urban councils. There is now no town council in Hitchin.<ref>{{cite web|title=Councils and Politics|url=http://www.hitchinforum.org.uk/about-hitchin/council-mp/|publisher=Hitchin Forum|accessdate=25 February 2012}}</ref> Residents elect 13 members to the [[North Hertfordshire District Council]]. There are five electoral wards in Hitchin: [[Bearton]], [[Highbury Ward|Highbury]], [[Hitchin Oughton|Oughton]], Priory and [[Walsworth]].\n\nThe town is represented in [[Parliament of the United Kingdom|Parliament]] by the constituency of [[Hitchin and Harpenden (UK Parliament constituency)|Hitchin and Harpenden]]. The incumbent [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative Party]] MP [[Bim Afolami]] was [[2017 United Kingdom general election|elected in 2017]]. Between 1983 and 1997 Hitchin was included in the constituency of [[North Hertfordshire (UK Parliament constituency)|North Hertfordshire]]. Before that it was in the constituency of [[Hitchin (UK Parliament constituency)|Hitchin]].\n\nIn the [[European Parliament]], Hitchin was represented by the [[East of England (European Parliament constituency)|East of England]] constituency, which elected 7 [[Member of the European Parliament|MEPs]]. Prior to 1999 and the adoption of [[proportional representation]], it was in the European constituency of [[Hertfordshire (European Parliament constituency)|Hertfordshire]].\n\n==Transport==\n\n=== Rail ===\n{{See also|Hitchin railway station}}\n[[Hitchin railway station]] is on the [[East Coast Main Line|Great Northern Line]], and is also on the [[Cambridge Line]] as the last stop before it diverges towards Cambridge, {{Convert|1.42|km|mi|abbr=}} to the north east of the Hitchin. The station is a call on services provided by [[Govia Thameslink Railway]] under its Great Northern and Thameslink brands. These provide direct connections to [[Cambridge railway station|Cambridge]], [[Letchworth Garden City railway station|Letchworth Garden City]], [[London King's Cross railway station|London Kings Cross]] and [[St Pancras railway station|St Pancras International]], [[Peterborough railway station|Peterborough]], [[Gatwick Airport railway station|Gatwick Airport]], [[Three Bridges railway station|Three Bridges]] and [[Brighton railway station|Brighton]]. Journeys to London and Cambridge typically take 33 minutes. Journeys to Stevenage is take 5 minutes, Peterborough 45 minutes, and Gatwick Airport 78 minutes.\n\nHitchin Rail Users Group serve as the local voluntary group actively consulting with train companies on behalf of local people.\n\n=== Road ===\nThe [[A505 road|A505]], A600 and [[A602 road|A602]] roads intersect in Hitchin, which is about {{convert|3|mi|km|0|spell=in}} from the [[A1(M) motorway]] and about {{convert|10|mi|km|0|spell=in}} from the [[M1 motorway]].\n\n=== Aviation ===\nHitchin is about {{Convert|14.48|km|mi|abbr=}} from Luton Airport, with a direct bus service linking the two. The connections are provided by the 39 minutes by National Express (number 787) or 46 minutes by Arriva in Herts and Essex (''100 Saphire'' services).\n\n==Education==\n{{see also|List of schools in Hertfordshire|Hertfordshire#Education}}\nThere are several primary schools in Hitchin. Secondary education is provided at [[Hitchin Girls' School]], [[Hitchin Boys' School]] and the [[The Priory School, Hitchin|Priory School]]. There is a campus of the [[North Hertfordshire College]] in Hitchin, and it is also the home of the [[Benslow Music Trust]] which provides music education for adults, while North Herts Music School adjoined to Hitchin Girls' School delivers music lessons & activities for children & young people.\n\n[https://northhertsmuseum.org/ North Hertfordshire Museum] has an extensive collection that tells the story of the town and wider area from prehistoric times. The [[British Schools Museum]] is housed in original Edwardian and Victorian school buildings.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-england-beds-bucks-herts-48693086|title=New museum finally opens after six-year argument|date=2019-07-06|access-date=2019-10-27|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n==Culture and community==\n[[File:Queen Mother Theatre Hitchin.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Queen Mother Theatre]] in the town]]\n[[File:Hitchin lavender fields.jpg|thumb|right|Lavender fields near Hitchin]]\nIn March 2013 a poll in ''[[The Times]]'' voted Hitchin the 9th best town in the UK in which to live.<ref>{{cite web|last=Burge|first=Laura|title=Hitchin Voted 9th Best Town In UK|url=http://www.thecomet.net/news/hitchin_voted_as_ninth_best_town_in_uk_1_1985557|work=The Comet 24|publisher=Archant Community Media Ltd|accessdate=20 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nHitchin hosts an annual Arts and Music Festival with over 100 events taking place during the month. Hitchin Festival includes picnics, concerts, theatre, ghost walks, art exhibitions, comedy club, talks, summer fetes and fireworks.<ref>{{cite web|last=Burge|first=Laura|title=Hitchin Festival to launch|url=http://www.thecomet.net/news/hitchin_festival_to_launch_1_947747|work=The Comet 24|publisher=Archant Community Media Ltd|accessdate=25 February 2012}}</ref> Since 2014, Hitchin has hosted the yarn festival, organised and run by members of Hitchin Stitchin.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\nMusic plays a very big part all year round with many venues hosting regular gigs. Hitchin Folk Club is one of the longest running and most respected clubs in the country meeting at The Sun Hotel on Sunday evenings; Hitchin Light Orchestra, Hitchin Symphony Orchestra and Hitchin Chamber Orchestra give regular concerts often in St Mary's Church and Hitchin Band perform around the country in brass band championship competition as well as the home town.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecomet.net/news/band-return-to-top-level-competition-1-5936320|title=Hitchin brass band to play at top level competition for first time in 33 years|last=Mountney|first=Dan|website=The Comet|language=en|access-date=2019-10-27}}</ref>\n\nAn independent music venue, Club 85, hosts an \"eclectic mix of contemporary bands and DJs\" in the area.<ref name=\":0\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.thetimes.co.uk/article/going-places-hitchin-0rswrzbdz|title=Going Places: Hitchin|last=Maslen|first=Cherry|date=2017-09-24|work=The Sunday Times|access-date=2019-10-27|language=en|issn=0956-1382}}</ref>\n\nThere are two small theatres in the town. [[The Market Theatre, Hitchin|The Market Theatre]], a professional theatre, has a year-round programme including comedy plays, thrillers, historical shows, jazz nights and cocktail evenings. The Market Theatre is known for its annual Adult Panto (running between December and May) which also tours nationally. Additionally, the [[Queen Mother Theatre]] hosts the town's Bancroft Players, Big Spirit Youth Theatre and occasional visiting companies as well as Hitchin Films in the Richard Whitmore Studio.\n\nHitchin Market remains one of the largest in the area with general markets every Tuesday and Saturday, a bric-a-brac and collectables market on Fridays, and a Sunday Car Boot. There are also Local Produce and Crafts specialist markets on the last Saturday of each month. A Lifestyle market is held on every second Saturday of the month, while infrequently there are occasional Art Markets. Hitchin Markets is also the venue for the annual Duck Race during Hitchin Festival.\n\nThe town centre has a wealth of independent retailers in food and drink and fashion and the historic core is a place to find niche boutiques. Since 1995, Hitchin has benefitted from award-winning town centre management and in 2009 established one of Hertfordshire's first Business Improvement Districts.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nIn 2019 the town's centre was a finalist for England in the [[Visa Inc.|Visa]]/[[Government of the United Kingdom|UK Government]] Great British High Street Awards.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecomet.net/news/hitchin-features-in-great-british-high-street-awards-2019-1-6211386|title=Hitchin's town centre nominated for national high street award|last=Thorburn|first=Jacob|website=The Comet|language=en|access-date=2019-10-27}}</ref>\n\nThere are a number of organisations for young people, including [[Air Training Corps|1066 Hitchin Squadron ATC]], [[Army Cadet Force|Hitchin Army Cadets]], [[Sea Cadet Corps|Sea Cadets Letchworth and Hitchin]], as well as various [[scouting]] groups.\n\nThe main burial ground for the town is [[Hitchin Cemetery]] on St. John's Road.\n\nHitchin is [[Twin towns and sister cities|twinned]] with:\n* [[File:Flag of France.svg|25px]] [[Nuits-St-Georges]], [[France]]\n* [[File:Flag of Germany.svg|25px]] [[Bingen am Rhein]], [[Germany]]\n\n==Sport in Hitchin==\n{{more citations needed|section|date=December 2017}}\n[[File:Top Field - Hitchin Town FC 02.jpg|thumb|[[Top Field]], the home ground of [[Hitchin Town F.C.]]]]\n\n=== Rugby Union ===\n{{See also|Hitchin Rugby Club}}\n[[Hitchin Rugby Club]] was founded in 1954 and competes in [[rugby union]] at all age levels within the Hitchin area. This includes teams at ages 7 to 12, 13 to 17, under 19s, seniors, over 35s, and a Ladies side.\n\nThe club's highlights have included playing at [[Twickenham]] in the final of the national Junior RFU Cup in 1993 and the establishment of the country's first Academy. Currently membership stands at over 500 people. The club are also active as a voluntary group with their community development programme.\n\n=== Association Football ===\n{{See also|Hitchin Town F.C.}}\n[[Hitchin Town F.C.]] was established in 1865 and later reformed in 1928. It is one of only three clubs who competed in the inaugural [[FA Cup]], paying the then \u00a325 entry fee (\u00a32,892 in 2019 adjusted for inflation),<ref name=\":1\">{{Citation|title=Half time rants & last minute equalisers {{!}} Experiencing a match day with Hitchin Town|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Wysl5ye3TF0|language=en|access-date=2019-10-27}}</ref> and continue to compete. They claim to be the second oldest club in English football, but some dispute this due to the reformation in the 1920s.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nThe side currently compete in the [[Southern Football League|Southern League Premier Division Central]], the seventh tier of English football. The club play at 4,554-capacity ground Top Field, in the north of the town, and came close to achieving promotion in the late 2010s, but have recently come into a more troubled spell.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\nTheir highlights include wins in the F.A. Cup against higher ranked sides Hereford United in 1994 and Bristol Rovers in 1995 during which period they developed a reputation for \"giant-killing\".<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/45863255|title=FA Cup fourth qualifying round: Cup heroes revisited, Houdini acts and a Barnet bus bonanza|date=2018-10-18|access-date=2019-10-27|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\nThe side count Hitchin-born England international [[Jack Wilshere]] among their supporters. Wilshire studied at the Priory School in the town and now runs a youth scheme called the Jack Wilshere Soccer School.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.thecomet.net/sport/football/exclusive-humble-jack-wilshere-backs-mark-burke-s-battling-hitchin-town-as-fa-cup-date-looms-with-bbc-set-to-broadcast-first-round-draw-from-top-field-if-canaries-progress-1-5743469|title=EXCLUSIVE: Humble Jack Wilshere backs Mark Burke's battling Hitchin Town as FA Cup date looms - with BBC set to broadcast first round draw from Top Field if Canaries progress|last=YOUSIF|first=EXCLUSIVE BY LAYTH|website=The Comet|language=en|access-date=2019-10-27}}</ref>\n\nThe club were featured by [[Sky Sports]] during their coverage of [[Non-League Day]] 2019 (taking place on 12 October each year), with the broadcaster following the match day experience at the club.<ref name=\":1\" />\n\n=== Other sports ===\nHitchin is also home to Blueharts Hockey Club, a leading club since 1946, with 7 men's teams and 7 women's team plus a thriving junior section.\n\nIt also houses [[Hitchin Cricket Club]], which has been an important cricket club within the area since 1866.\n\nHitchin Swimming Club are based locally and competes at local, county and regional level.\n\nThe Hitchin Nomads Cycling Club, which caters for many competitive and non-competitive cycling disciplines, was formed in the town in 1931. It is affiliated to British Cycling, the Cyclists' Touring Club, Cycling time trials and local cycling associations. Notable former members include pre-eminent cycling [[travel writer]] [[Harold Briercliffe]] and Max Pendleton, father of [[Olympic Games|Olympic]] gold-medallist and [[Cycling World Championship|track cycling World Champion]] [[Victoria Pendleton]].\n\nFormed in 2003 and known as FVS TRI until November 2009, Team Trisports is a Hitchin-based triathlon club. In addition to triathlon, the club an England Athletics and British Cycling affiliate.\n\nHitchin Running Club was formed in 2008 and is one of the most popular clubs in the town. They enjoy a large fan base and many local people of all abilities take part in the social activities. They are based at the rugby club and are a not for profit organisation.\n\n==Districts of Hitchin==\n* [[Bearton]]\n* [[Benslow]]\n* [[Poets Estate (Hitchin)|Poets Estate]]\n* [[Purwell]]\n* [[Sunnyside (Hitchin)|Sunnyside]]\n* [[Walsworth]]\n* [[West Hitchin]]\n* [[Westmill (Hitchin)|Westmill]]\n\n==Nearby settlements==\n[[Ickleford]] is a village situated on the northern outskirts of Hitchin, and to the south is [[St Ippolyts]], [[Charlton, Hertfordshire|Charlton]] and [[Gosmore]]. The nearest towns are [[Letchworth]], [[Baldock]], [[Stevenage]] and [[Luton]].\n\n==Notable people who have lived in Hitchin==\n{{more citations needed section|date=January 2017}}\n{{See also|Category:People from Hitchin}}\n{{columns-list|colwidth=30em|* [[BadBoyYardie]], gangster rapper, producer, businessman, entrepreneur\n* [[Dorothy Atkinson]], actress\n* [[Guillem Balagu\u00e9]], Spanish football journalist\n* [[James Bay (singer)|James Bay]], musician\n* [[Tom Bentley]], philanthropist\n* [[Henry Bessemer]], engineer\n* [[Jennie Bond]], journalist\n* [[Sally Bretton]], actress\n* [[Harold Briercliffe]], cyclist and author\n* [[Drewe Broughton]], footballer\n* [[Edward Chapman (publisher)|Edward Chapman]], publisher\n* [[George Chapman]], poet\n* [[Oliver Cheshire]], fashion model\n* [[Chris Cleaver]], footballer\n* [[Bill Coleman (cricketer)|Bill Coleman]], cricketer\n* [[Mary Angela Dickens]], novelist and granddaughter of [[Charles Dickens]]\n* [[Monica Dickens]], novelist and great granddaughter of [[Charles Dickens]]\n* [[Karl Duguid]], footballer\n* [[Willie Duncan]], musician\n* [[Gail Emms]], badminton player\n* [[Ross Flitney]], footballer\n* [[Mathew Gates]], figure skater\n* [[Martin Gordon]], musician\n* [[F.L. Griggs]], etcher\n* [[Henry Hawkins, 1st Baron Brampton]], judge\n* [[E O Higgins]], author\n* [[Reginald Hine]], solicitor and historian\n* [[Paul Jesson]], actor\n* [[Roy Kettle]], author\n* [[Thea King]], clarinettist\n* [[Dave Kitson]], footballer\n* [[Kane Kramer]], inventor of the digital audio player\n* [[Frank Launder]], film director\n* [[Joseph Lister, 1st Baron Lister|Joseph Lister]], pioneer of antiseptic surgery\n* [[John Lloyd (graphic designer)|John Lloyd]], co-founder of the international design consultancy Lloyd Northover.\n* [[Gavin McInnes]], writer, political commentator \n* [[Sally Biddulph|Sally Mules]], journalist and presenter\n* [[Elaine Murray]], Scottish politician\n* Dixie Newberry, National darts champion 1949-1950\n* [[Robert Newman (comedian)|Robert Newman]], comedian\n* [[David Noble (footballer, born 1982)|David Noble]], footballer\n* [[Arvind Parmar]], tennis player\n* [[Ian Perkins]], Musician\n* [[Kevin Phillips (footballer)|Kevin Phillips]], footballer\n* [[Richard Shannon]], chief of advertising and tourism in Lloret de Mar\n* [[Kevin Pilkington]], footballer\n* [[Ian Poulter]], golfer\n* [[Pam Rhodes]], [[BBC]] TV presenter<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thespeakersagency.com/speaker/pam-rhodes/ |title=Pam Rhodes |work=The Speakers Agency |accessdate=10 September 2017 }}</ref>\n* [[Helen Richardson-Walsh]], England and Great Britain hockey player. Multiple Olympic medalist, EuroHockey Nations champion and Champions challenge winner. \n* [[Michael Robbins]], actor\n* [[Robert Tor Russell]], architect of [[New Delhi]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.oxfordartonline.com/subscriber/article/grove/art/T074580?q=Robert+Tor+Russell&search=quick&pos=1&_start=1#firsthit |title=Russell, Robert Tor in Oxford Art Online |publisher=www.oxfordartonline.com |accessdate=6 September 2010 }} (requires login or UK library card)</ref>\n* [[Martin Savage (actor)|Martin Savage]], actor\n* [[Steve Sheppard]],  B.B.C. Cricket and football commentator and owner of One World Music\n* [[Valerie Singleton]], TV presenter\n* [[Richard Walker (angler)|Richard Walker]], angler\n* [[Diana Wallis]], politician (MEP)\n* [[Kristiina Wheeler]], an English-Finnish singer\n* [[Richard Whitmore]], former newsreader\n* Sir [[Frank Whittle]], inventor of the jet engine\n* [[Jack Wilshere]], footballer\n* [[Henry Wood (conductor)|Henry Wood]], conductor\n* Second Lieutenant [[Frank Edward Young (VC)|Frank Young VC]], recipient of the [[Victoria Cross]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.bedfordregiment.org.uk/Hertsrgt/youngvc.html|title=Second Lieutenant Frank Edward Young VC|publisher=www.bedfordregiment.org.uk|accessdate=2 June 2013}}</ref>\n* [[Gary Younge]], journalist\n* [[The Bleach Boys]], Punk Band dating from 1976}}\n\n==Filmography==\nMike Leigh\u2019s 1982 film \u2018\u2019[[Home Sweet Home (1982 film)|Home Sweet Home]]\u2019\u2019 for BBC Television was set in Hitchin. [[File:Hitchin Market Square 2018.jpg|thumb|right|Various scenes in ''[[Doctor Foster (TV series)|Doctor Foster]]'' were filmed at the Market Square in Hitchin]]\nPart of the 2010 BBC TV series ''[[Just William (2010 TV serial)|Just William]]'' was filmed at the [[British Schools Museum]].<ref>{{cite web|last=Judge|first=Ann|title=The BBC 'Just William' at Hitchin British Schools|url=http://www.hertsmemories.org.uk/page_id__2258_path__0p34p109p.aspx|work=Herts Memories|publisher=[[Hertfordshire County Council]]|accessdate=25 February 2012}}</ref>\n\nScenes from the BBC drama series ''[[Doctor Foster (TV series)|Doctor Foster]]'' were filmed in Hitchin, as well as the Channel 4 series ''[[Humans (TV series)|Humans]]''.{{citation needed|date=March 2019}}\n\n==Miscellaneous==\nIn 1960 Hitchin [[Urban District Council]] was the first in Britain to introduce 'black bags' for refuse collection.{{citation needed|date=December 2017}}\n\n[[Queen Elizabeth The Queen Mother|Elizabeth the Queen Mother]]'s birth in 1900 was registered at Hitchin, which is a few miles from her parent's [[English country house]], [[St Paul's Walden Bury]], where she spent much of her childhood.\n\nThe 1951 book ''[[My Turn to Make the Tea]]'' by [[Monica Dickens]] is set in Hitchin (renamed Downingham in the book).\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Commons category|Hitchin}}\n{{wikivoyage|Hitchin}}\n* [http://www.hitchinhistoricals.org.uk/ Hitchin Historical Society]\n* [http://www.hitchinsociety.org.uk/ Hitchin Society]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20170709150242/http://www.alehouses.info/hitchin/ Historical Map of Hitchin Pubs], an interactive map of Hitchin public houses both current and closed.\n* {{Cite EB1911|wstitle=Hitchin|short=x}}\n\n{{Hertfordshire}}\n{{Civil parishes of Hertfordshire}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2017}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Hitchin| ]]\n[[Category:Towns in Hertfordshire]]\n[[Category:Market towns in Hertfordshire]]\n[[Category:North Hertfordshire District]]\n", "name_user": "Crouch, Swale", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eExternal links:Category:Unparished areas in Hertfordshire", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Hitchin"}
{"title_page": "Willy Bo Richardson", "text_new": "{{Infobox artist\n| name = Willy Bo Richardson\n| image = File:Willy Bo Richardson Studio.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| alt = Willy Bo Richardson\n| caption = Willy Bo Richardson\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1974|6|8|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Santa Fe, New Mexico]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = \n| field = Painting\n| training = [[University of Wisconsin]], [[UT Austin]], and [[Pratt Institute]]\n| movement =\n| works =\n| patrons =\n| awards =\n| website = \n}}\n\n'''Willy Bo Richardson''' (born June 8, 1974) is an American artist from [[Santa Fe, New Mexico]]. Richardson is regarded as one of many contemporary painters revisiting late Modernism.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Dad why do you paint Stripes?|url = http://www.pyragraph.com/2016/11/dad-why-do-you-paint-stripes/|website = Pyragraph}}</ref>  Describing his paintings as \u201cphilosophy in motion,\u201d Richardson works solely within the framework of vertical strokes. He exhibits his paintings internationally.<ref>{{Cite web|title = The Soul of Santa Fe|url = http://issuu.com/willyrichardson/docs/destinasian/3?e=8101390/2242324|website = [[DestinAsian]]|access-date = 2016-01-14|page = 108}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = FROM DARKNESS: LIGHT|url = https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1609937651.html|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160316033331/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1609937651.html|url-status = dead|archive-date = March 16, 2016|website = Santa Fe Reporter (subscription required)|access-date = 2016-01-14|date = November 5, 2008|last = Fischer|first = Zane}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nRichardson was born in [[Santa Fe, NM]]. His father was a master wood-worker, and his mother founded the first mediation center in the Southwest. He studied at [[UW Madison]] and received a BA from [[University of Texas at Austin]]. While at UT Austin, he counted [[Peter Saul]] among his teachers.\n\nLiving in Philadelphia in 1997, he was writing and painting. Richardson jokes, \"I wrote a really bad coming of age novel, and the next year I checked myself in to graduate school for painting at [[Pratt Institute]]\" in Brooklyn. He received an MFA there in 2000. He and his wife lived in New York City for a decade.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Willy Bo Richardson: Artist Profile|url = https://santafeartstudio.com/profiles/willy-bo-richardson-artist-profile/|website = Santa Fe Art Studio}}</ref> He worked as a painting technician at [[Cooper Union]] from 2001-2007. \n\n==Career==\nRichardson was a faculty member at [[Santa Fe University of Art and Design]] from 2009-2016.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Studio Arts Faculty|url = http://santafeuniversity.edu/academics/studio-arts/faculty/|website = Santa Fe University of Art and Design|access-date = 2016-01-14}}</ref> In 2011 his work was included in the exhibition at Jason McCoy Gallery in New York titled, \"70 Years of Abstract Painting \u2013 Excerpts\".  The show assembled works by a selection of modern and contemporary painters, including [[Josef Albers]], [[Hans Hofmann]] and [[Jackson Pollock]]. In 2012 he showed a body of work in the exhibition \"Watercolors\u201d\" at the Phillips de Pury headquarters in Chelsea New York.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Willy Bo Richardson - Watercolors - galleryIntell|url = http://www.galleryintell.com/willy-bo-richardson-watercolors/|website = galleryIntell|access-date = 2016-01-14|language = en-US|last = Nazarevskaia|first = Kristina}}</ref> In 2014 Richardson was selected to be one of the [[SITE Santa Fe]] SPREAD finalists. His work and vision was featured on the [[KNME-TV]] PBS weekly arts series \u00a1COLORES!.<ref>{{cite web|title=Willy Bo Richardson, The Impressionists, Regional Theater, Jack Ross|url=http://www.newmexicopbs.org/productions/colores/february-7-2014/|publisher=New Mexico PBS|accessdate=14 January 2016}}</ref> Richardson's painting titled \"Number 1,\" 1999 was acquired by the [[Albuquerque Museum]] in 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.unm.edu/news/tamarind-institute-presents-no-modifiers-an-exhibition|title=Tamarind Presents: No Modifiers. Featured works created by graduate students and professional guest artists|last=|first=|date=|website=The University of New Mexico|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. He was a guest artist at the [[Tamarind Institute]] at the University of New Mexico in 2019. Richardson is represented by [[Richard Levy Gallery]] in Albuquerque.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{officialwebsite|http://willyborichardson.com/}}\n* Wright, Margaret. [http://adobeairstream.com/art/painters-point-way-richard-levy-gallery/ Painters Point the Way at Richard Levy Gallery] Adobe Airstream, August\u2013September 2014 Edition.\n* LaSalle-Hopkins, Patti. [https://www.newmexico.org/nmmagazine/articles/post/on-the-line/ On the Line] New Mexico Magazine, April 2018 Edition.\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Richardson, Willy Bo}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American painters]]\n[[Category:American male painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century American painters]]\n[[Category:Abstract painters]]\n[[Category:Artists from Santa Fe, New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Painters from New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Southwestern artists|New Mexico]]\n[[Category:People from New Mexico by occupation]]\n[[Category:Artists from New Mexico]]\n\n\n{{US-painter-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox artist\n| name = Willy Bo Richardson\n| image = File:Willy Bo Richardson Studio.jpg\n| imagesize = \n| alt = Willy Bo Richardson\n| caption = Willy Bo Richardson\n| birth_name = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1974|6|8|mf=y}}\n| birth_place = [[Santa Fe, New Mexico]]\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = \n| field = Painting\n| training = [[University of Wisconsin]], [[UT Austin]], and [[Pratt Institute]]\n| movement =\n| works =\n| patrons =\n| awards =\n| website = \n}}\n\n'''Willy Bo Richardson''' (born June 8, 1974) is an American artist from [[Santa Fe, New Mexico]]. Richardson is regarded as one of many contemporary painters revisiting late Modernism.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Dad why do you paint Stripes?|url = http://www.pyragraph.com/2016/11/dad-why-do-you-paint-stripes/|website = Pyragraph}}</ref>  Describing his paintings as \u201cphilosophy in motion,\u201d Richardson works solely within the framework of vertical strokes. He exhibits his paintings internationally.<ref>{{Cite web|title = The Soul of Santa Fe|url = http://issuu.com/willyrichardson/docs/destinasian/3?e=8101390/2242324|website = [[DestinAsian]]|access-date = 2016-01-14|page = 108}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = FROM DARKNESS: LIGHT|url = https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1609937651.html|archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20160316033331/https://www.highbeam.com/doc/1P3-1609937651.html|url-status = dead|archive-date = March 16, 2016|website = Santa Fe Reporter (subscription required)|access-date = 2016-01-14|date = November 5, 2008|last = Fischer|first = Zane}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and education==\nRichardson was born in [[Santa Fe, NM]]. His father was a master wood-worker, and his mother founded the first mediation center in the Southwest. He studied at [[UW Madison]] and received a BA from [[University of Texas at Austin]]. While at UT Austin, he counted [[Peter Saul]] among his teachers.\n\nLiving in Philadelphia in 1997, he was writing and painting. Richardson jokes, \"I wrote a really bad coming of age novel, and the next year I checked myself in to graduate school for painting at [[Pratt Institute]]\" in Brooklyn. He received an MFA there in 2000. He and his wife lived in New York City for a decade.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Willy Bo Richardson: Artist Profile|url = https://santafeartstudio.com/profiles/willy-bo-richardson-artist-profile/|website = Santa Fe Art Studio}}</ref> He worked as a painting technician at [[Cooper Union]] from 2001-2007. \n\n==Career==\nRichardson was a painting tech at [[Cooper Union]]  between 2001-2007 and faculty member at [[Santa Fe University of Art and Design]] from 2009-2016.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Studio Arts Faculty|url = http://santafeuniversity.edu/academics/studio-arts/faculty/|website = Santa Fe University of Art and Design|access-date = 2016-01-14}}</ref> In 2011 his work was included in the exhibition at Jason McCoy Gallery in New York titled, \"70 Years of Abstract Painting \u2013 Excerpts\".  The show assembled works by a selection of modern and contemporary painters, including [[Josef Albers]], [[Hans Hofmann]] and [[Jackson Pollock]]. In 2012 he showed a body of work in the exhibition \"Watercolors\u201d\" at the Phillips de Pury headquarters in Chelsea New York.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Willy Bo Richardson - Watercolors - galleryIntell|url = http://www.galleryintell.com/willy-bo-richardson-watercolors/|website = galleryIntell|access-date = 2016-01-14|language = en-US|last = Nazarevskaia|first = Kristina}}</ref> In 2014 Richardson was selected to be one of the [[SITE Santa Fe]] SPREAD finalists. His work and vision was featured on the [[KNME-TV]] PBS weekly arts series \u00a1COLORES!.<ref>{{cite web|title=Willy Bo Richardson, The Impressionists, Regional Theater, Jack Ross|url=http://www.newmexicopbs.org/productions/colores/february-7-2014/|publisher=New Mexico PBS|accessdate=14 January 2016}}</ref> Richardson's painting titled \"Number 1,\" 1999 was acquired by the [[Albuquerque Museum]] in 2018<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.unm.edu/news/tamarind-institute-presents-no-modifiers-an-exhibition|title=Tamarind Presents: No Modifiers. Featured works created by graduate students and professional guest artists|last=|first=|date=|website=The University of New Mexico|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>. He was a guest artist at the [[Tamarind Institute]] at the University of New Mexico in 2019. Richardson is represented by [[Richard Levy Gallery]] in Albuquerque.\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{officialwebsite|http://willyborichardson.com/}}\n* Wright, Margaret. [http://adobeairstream.com/art/painters-point-way-richard-levy-gallery/ Painters Point the Way at Richard Levy Gallery] Adobe Airstream, August\u2013September 2014 Edition.\n* LaSalle-Hopkins, Patti. [https://www.newmexico.org/nmmagazine/articles/post/on-the-line/ On the Line] New Mexico Magazine, April 2018 Edition.\n\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Richardson, Willy Bo}}\n[[Category:1974 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:20th-century American painters]]\n[[Category:American male painters]]\n[[Category:21st-century American painters]]\n[[Category:Abstract painters]]\n[[Category:Artists from Santa Fe, New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Painters from New Mexico]]\n[[Category:Southwestern artists|New Mexico]]\n[[Category:People from New Mexico by occupation]]\n[[Category:Artists from New Mexico]]\n\n\n{{US-painter-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Badabara", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eCareer", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Willy_Bo_Richardson"}
{"title_page": "Lawrence R. Goldfarb", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Lawrence Goldfarb\n| image         = Lawrence Goldfarb.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Lawrence Goldfarb\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1958|11|21}}\n| birth_place   = [[Queens]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|NY]]\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = American\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = [[Hedge fund]] manager and [[CEO]]\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = [[LRG Capital Group]], [[LRG Racing]]\n| notable_works = \n}}\n'''Lawrence R. Goldfarb''' (born November 21, 1958 in [[Queens]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|NY]]) is an American [[hedge fund]] manager, and [[CEO]] and founding partner of the [[LRG Capital Group]]. Goldfarb also owns [[LRG Racing]], which competed in the [[American Federation of Motorcyclists]].\n\n==Education==\n\nGoldfarb grew up in the [[New York City]] boroughs outside Manhattan and attended [[Forest Hills High School (New York)|Forest Hills High School]]. Following high school, he attended [[George Washington University]] and earned a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in International Economics, and graduated in 1981.\n\nIn 1984, Goldfarb graduated ''cum laude'' with a Juris Doctor degree from [[Georgetown University Law School]] and wrote for the [[Georgetown Law Journal]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Georgetown Law - Classmates Search|url=http://www.law.georgetown.edu/alumni/class/1984/classmatesSearch.cfm?class=84|publisher=Georgetown University Law Center|accessdate=16 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Alumni Affairs: 1984 Facebook|url=http://www.law.georgetown.edu/alumni/class/1984/facebook/fbpage10.html|publisher=Georgetown University Law Center|accessdate=16 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\nGoldfarb began his career as a tax attorney for [[Milbank, Tweed, Hadley & McCloy]] and subsequently became a tax analyst with [[Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher & Flom]], where he specialized in financings, mergers and recapitalizations. Afterwards, Goldfarb moved to [[San Francisco, California]] and joined [[Credit Suisse First Boston]] Corporation as a Partner and Director of the Mergers and Acquisitions Group. In 1998 he formed [[BayStar Capital]] Management, LLC, a vehicle in which he could fund growth oriented, small capitalization, and publicly traded companies. Through Baystar, Goldfarb funded and invested in a variety of companies such as [[World Online]] and [[XM Satellite Radio]].<ref>{{cite web|title=XM Radio Announces $450 Million Financing Package|url=http://investor.sirius.com/releasedetail-XM.cfm?releaseid=333116|publisher=XM Satellite Radio|accessdate=9 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=XM RADIO CLOSES $475 MILLION FINANCING PACKAGE|url=http://investor.siriusxm.com/releasedetail-xm.cfm?ReleaseID=334175|publisher=XM Satellite Radio|accessdate=9 May 2012}}</ref> Goldfarb was well known for being one of the most foremost investors and experts in [[Private investment in public equity]], also known as PIPEs.<ref>{{cite web|title=BayStar Capital Featured in Private Equity Week Article|url=http://www.lrgcapital.com/news-article.php?id=100&keywords=BayStar_Capital_Featured_in_Private_Equity_Week_Article|publisher=Private Equity Week|accessdate=9 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Lawrence Goldfarb Contributes Chapter to New Bloomberg Press PIPEs Book|url=http://www.lrgcapital.com/news-article.php?id=135&keywords=Lawrence_Goldfarb_Contributes_Chapter_to_New_Bloomberg_Press_PIPEs_Book|publisher=LRG Capital Group|accessdate=9 May 2012}}</ref> In 2005, he founded [[LRG Capital Group]] in [[Larkspur, California]] where he served as CEO until July 2011 when he announced his retirement from active management of the company to focus on philanthropic activities.<ref>{{cite web |title=LRG Capital Group Founder and CEO Lawrence Goldfarb Retires From the Company to Focus on Philanthropic Foundation and Other Interests |url=http://www.lrgcapital.com/news-article.php?id=222&keywords=LRG_Capital_Group_Founder_and_CEO_Lawrence_Goldfarb_Retires_From_the_Company_to_Focus_on_Philanthropic_Foundation_and_Other_Interests |publisher=LRG Capital |accessdate=13 January 2012}}</ref> Goldfarb currently serves as a board member and West Coast Director of AutismAid, an organization dedicated to assisting and fundraising for other autism non-profit organizations.<ref>{{cite web|title=About Us|url=http://autismaid.org/index-1.html|publisher=AutismAid|accessdate=29 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Pressey|first=Debra|title=Organizers plan to raise money for community autism agencies|url=http://www.news-gazette.com/news/education/2012-03-15/organizers-plan-raise-money-community-autism-agencies.html|publisher=The News-Gazette|accessdate=29 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Larry Goldfarb & Tim Welsh Create AutismAid|url=http://www.marketwire.com/press-release/lawrence-larry-goldfarb-tim-welsh-create-autismaid-unify-support-autism-community-1631299.htm|publisher=MarketWire|accessdate=13 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, he has also served on the boards of various non-profits and organizations.<ref>{{cite web |title=YTA Staff and Board |url=http://www.youthtennis.org/About_Us/YTA_Staff_and_Board.htm |publisher=Youth Tennis Advantage |accessdate=3 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=142 Throckmorton Theatre Announces New Board Members |url=http://millvalley.patch.com/announcements/142-throckmorton-theatre-announces-new-board-members |publisher=Mill Valley Patch |accessdate=3 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Marin History Museum Announces New Board Members |url=http://sanrafael.patch.com/announcements/marin-history-museum-announces-new-board-members |publisher=San Rafael Patch |accessdate=3 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Company Bios |url=http://www.joetoucandiabetesproject.org/bios_larry.html |publisher=The Joe Toucan Diabetes Project |accessdate=3 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Larry Goldfarb Elected to the Easter Seals Board of Directors |url=http://noca.easterseals.com/site/DocServer/Larry_Goldfarb_new_board_member_6-7-10.press_release.pdf?docID=138744 |publisher=Easter Seals |accessdate=3 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==SEC settlement==\n\nOn March 1, 2011 the [[Securities and Exchange Commission]] (SEC) alleged that Goldfarb and his company illegally diverted $12 million from a hedge fund side pocket investment to other entities he controlled.<ref name=sec2011>{{cite web|title=SEC Charges Bay Area Hedge Fund Manager With Misappropriating \"Side Pocketed\" Assets |url=https://www.sec.gov/news/press/2011/2011-54.htm |publisher=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission|SEC]] |accessdate=2 March 2011}}</ref> On March 1, 2011, without admitting or denying allegations, Goldfarb settled with the SEC.<ref name=SEC2011>{{cite web |last=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission|SEC]] |title=Securities and Exchange Commission v. Lawrence R. Goldfarb et al., CV-11-0938-DMR (U.S. District Court for the Northern District of California, filed March 1, 2011) |url=https://www.sec.gov/litigation/litreleases/2011/lr21870.htm |publisher=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission|SEC]] |accessdate=13 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn June 20, 2012, the Court found that the defendants [Goldfarb] were in breach of the Final Judgment by failing to pay the disgorgement amounts ordered. The Court also found that defendants had failed to establish a good faith effort to fulfil their disgorgement obligations because, among other things, they used available funds for large personal expenses such as courtside seats to Golden State Warriors games, charters of aircraft for personal trips, Goldfarb's mortgage payment and numerous personal vacations, rather than to pay disgorgement.<ref>[http://www.hedgeweek.com/2012/06/27/168923/court-finds-hf-manager-civil-contempt-failing-pay-usd12m-defrauded-investors News account of Civil Contempt judgement]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[LRG Capital Funds]]\n*[[LRG Capital Group]]\n*[[LRG Racing]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.lawrencegoldfarb.com}}\n*{{LinkedIn URL | https://www.linkedin.com/in/lawrence-goldfarb-1b2424159 }}\n*{{Pinterest|lrgoldfarb}}\n*[https://judicialreformfoundation.org/about/ Biography] (The Lawrence Goldfarb Judicial Foundation) \n*[http://www.lrgcapital.com/ LRG Capital]\n*[http://www.lrgracing.com/ LRG Racing]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Goldfarb, Lawrence}}\n[[Category:American chief executives of financial services companies]]\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:George Washington University alumni]]\n[[Category:Georgetown University Law Center alumni]]\n[[Category:People associated with Milbank, Tweed, Hadley & McCloy]]\n[[Category:Forest Hills High School (New York) alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name          = Lawrence Goldfarb\n| image         = Lawrence Goldfarb.jpg\n| alt           = \n| caption       = Lawrence Goldfarb\n| birth_name    = \n| birth_date    = {{Birth date and age|1958|11|21}}\n| birth_place   = [[Queens]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|NY]]\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| nationality   = American\n| other_names   = \n| occupation    = [[Hedge fund]] manager and former [[CEO]]\n| years_active  = \n| known_for     = [[LRG Capital Group]], [[LRG Racing]]\n| notable_works = \n}}\n'''Lawrence R. Goldfarb''' (born November 21, 1958 in [[Queens]], [[New York City]], [[New York (state)|NY]]) is an American [[hedge fund]] manager, and [[CEO]] and founding partner of the [[LRG Capital Group]]. Goldfarb also owns [[LRG Racing]], which competed in the [[American Federation of Motorcyclists]].\n\n==Education==\n\nGoldfarb grew up in the [[New York City]] boroughs outside Manhattan and attended [[Forest Hills High School (New York)|Forest Hills High School]]. Following high school, he attended [[George Washington University]] and earned a [[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]] in International Economics, and graduated in 1981.\n\nIn 1984, Goldfarb graduated ''cum laude'' with a Juris Doctor degree from [[Georgetown University Law School]] and wrote for the [[Georgetown Law Journal]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Georgetown Law - Classmates Search|url=http://www.law.georgetown.edu/alumni/class/1984/classmatesSearch.cfm?class=84|publisher=Georgetown University Law Center|accessdate=16 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Alumni Affairs: 1984 Facebook|url=http://www.law.georgetown.edu/alumni/class/1984/facebook/fbpage10.html|publisher=Georgetown University Law Center|accessdate=16 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==Career==\n\nGoldfarb began his career as a tax attorney for [[Milbank, Tweed, Hadley & McCloy]] and subsequently became a tax analyst with [[Skadden, Arps, Slate, Meagher & Flom]], where he specialized in financings, mergers and recapitalizations. Afterwards, Goldfarb moved to [[San Francisco, California]] and joined [[Credit Suisse First Boston]] Corporation as a Partner and Director of the Mergers and Acquisitions Group. In 1998 he formed [[BayStar Capital]] Management, LLC, a vehicle in which he could fund growth oriented, small capitalization, and publicly traded companies. Through Baystar, Goldfarb funded and invested in a variety of companies such as [[World Online]] & [[XM Satellite Radio]].<ref>{{cite web|title=XM Radio Announces $450 Million Financing Package|url=http://investor.sirius.com/releasedetail-XM.cfm?releaseid=333116|publisher=XM Satellite Radio|accessdate=9 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=XM RADIO CLOSES $475 MILLION FINANCING PACKAGE|url=http://investor.siriusxm.com/releasedetail-xm.cfm?ReleaseID=334175|publisher=XM Satellite Radio|accessdate=9 May 2012}}</ref> Goldfarb was well known for being one of the most foremost investors and experts in [[Private investment in public equity]], also known as PIPEs.<ref>{{cite web|title=BayStar Capital Featured in Private Equity Week Article|url=http://www.lrgcapital.com/news-article.php?id=100&keywords=BayStar_Capital_Featured_in_Private_Equity_Week_Article|publisher=Private Equity Week|accessdate=9 May 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Lawrence Goldfarb Contributes Chapter to New Bloomberg Press PIPEs Book|url=http://www.lrgcapital.com/news-article.php?id=135&keywords=Lawrence_Goldfarb_Contributes_Chapter_to_New_Bloomberg_Press_PIPEs_Book|publisher=LRG Capital Group|accessdate=9 May 2012}}</ref> In 2005, he founded [[LRG Capital Group]] in [[Larkspur, California]] where he served as CEO until July 2011 when he announced his retirement from active management of the company to focus on philanthropic activities.<ref>{{cite web |title=LRG Capital Group Founder and CEO Lawrence Goldfarb Retires From the Company to Focus on Philanthropic Foundation and Other Interests |url=http://www.lrgcapital.com/news-article.php?id=222&keywords=LRG_Capital_Group_Founder_and_CEO_Lawrence_Goldfarb_Retires_From_the_Company_to_Focus_on_Philanthropic_Foundation_and_Other_Interests |publisher=LRG Capital |accessdate=13 January 2012}}</ref> Goldfarb currently serves as a board member and West Coast Director of AutismAid, an organization dedicated to assisting and fundraising for other autism non-profit organizations.<ref>{{cite web|title=About Us|url=http://autismaid.org/index-1.html|publisher=AutismAid|accessdate=29 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last=Pressey|first=Debra|title=Organizers plan to raise money for community autism agencies|url=http://www.news-gazette.com/news/education/2012-03-15/organizers-plan-raise-money-community-autism-agencies.html|publisher=The News-Gazette|accessdate=29 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Larry Goldfarb & Tim Welsh Create AutismAid|url=http://www.marketwire.com/press-release/lawrence-larry-goldfarb-tim-welsh-create-autismaid-unify-support-autism-community-1631299.htm|publisher=MarketWire|accessdate=13 March 2012}}</ref>\n\nAdditionally, he has also served on the boards of various non-profits and organizations.<ref>{{cite web |title=YTA Staff and Board |url=http://www.youthtennis.org/About_Us/YTA_Staff_and_Board.htm |publisher=Youth Tennis Advantage |accessdate=3 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=142 Throckmorton Theatre Announces New Board Members |url=http://millvalley.patch.com/announcements/142-throckmorton-theatre-announces-new-board-members |publisher=Mill Valley Patch |accessdate=3 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Marin History Museum Announces New Board Members |url=http://sanrafael.patch.com/announcements/marin-history-museum-announces-new-board-members |publisher=San Rafael Patch |accessdate=3 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Company Bios |url=http://www.joetoucandiabetesproject.org/bios_larry.html |publisher=The Joe Toucan Diabetes Project |accessdate=3 April 2012}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Larry Goldfarb Elected to the Easter Seals Board of Directors |url=http://noca.easterseals.com/site/DocServer/Larry_Goldfarb_new_board_member_6-7-10.press_release.pdf?docID=138744 |publisher=Easter Seals |accessdate=3 April 2012}}</ref>\n\n==SEC settlement==\n\nOn March 1, 2011 the [[Securities and Exchange Commission]] (SEC) alleged that Goldfarb and his company illegally diverted $12 million from a hedge fund side pocket investment to other entities he controlled.<ref name=sec2011>{{cite web|title=SEC Charges Bay Area Hedge Fund Manager With Misappropriating \"Side Pocketed\" Assets |url=https://www.sec.gov/news/press/2011/2011-54.htm |publisher=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission|SEC]] |accessdate=2 March 2011}}</ref> On March 1, 2011, without admitting or denying allegations, Goldfarb settled with the SEC.<ref name=SEC2011>{{cite web |last=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission|SEC]] |title=Securities and Exchange Commission v. Lawrence R. Goldfarb et al., CV-11-0938-DMR (U.S. District Court for the Northern District of California, filed March 1, 2011) |url=https://www.sec.gov/litigation/litreleases/2011/lr21870.htm |publisher=[[U.S. Securities and Exchange Commission|SEC]] |accessdate=13 January 2012}}</ref>\n\nOn June 20, 2012, the Court found that the defendants [Goldfarb] were in breach of the Final Judgment by failing to pay the disgorgement amounts ordered. The Court also found that defendants had failed to establish a good faith effort to fulfil their disgorgement obligations because, among other things, they used available funds for large personal expenses such as courtside seats to Golden State Warriors games, charters of aircraft for personal trips, Goldfarb's mortgage payment and numerous personal vacations, rather than to pay disgorgement.<ref>[http://www.hedgeweek.com/2012/06/27/168923/court-finds-hf-manager-civil-contempt-failing-pay-usd12m-defrauded-investors News account of Civil Contempt judgement]</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[LRG Capital Funds]]\n*[[LRG Capital Group]]\n*[[LRG Racing]]\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Official website|http://www.lawrencegoldfarb.com}}\n*{{LinkedIn URL | https://www.linkedin.com/in/lawrence-goldfarb-1b2424159 }}\n*{{Pinterest|lrgoldfarb}}\n*[https://judicialreformfoundation.org/about/ Biography] (The Lawrence Goldfarb Judicial Foundation) \n*[http://www.lrgcapital.com/ LRG Capital]\n*[http://www.lrgracing.com/ LRG Racing]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Goldfarb, Lawrence}}\n[[Category:American chief executives of financial services companies]]\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:George Washington University alumni]]\n[[Category:Georgetown University Law Center alumni]]\n[[Category:People associated with Milbank, Tweed, Hadley & McCloy]]\n[[Category:Forest Hills High School (New York) alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Gabrielsky1972", "label": "safe", "comment": "punctuation", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Lawrence_R._Goldfarb"}
{"title_page": "2020 coronavirus pandemic in Azerbaijan", "text_new": "{{current||ongoing pandemic}}\n{{short description|Details of ongoing viral pandemic in Azerbaijan}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = 2020 coronavirus pandemic in Azerbaijan\n| map1            = COVID-19 pandemic Cases in Azerbaijan.svg\n| legend1         = Number of confirmed cases by regions<br>(as of 5 April): {{legend|#FFD5D5|Confirmed 1}}\n{{legend|#FF8080|Confirmed 2~5}}\n{{legend|#FF2A2A|Confirmed 6~10}}\n{{legend|#D40000|Confirmed 11~100}}\n{{legend|#800000|Confirmed \u2265100}}\n| map2            = \n| legend2         = \n| map3            = \n| legend3         = \n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Azerbaijan]]\n| first_case      = [[Baku]]\n| arrival_date    = 28 February 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=02|day1=28|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          = [[Wuhan]], [[Hubei]], [[China]]; [[Iran]]\n| recovery_cases  = 712<ref name=\"counter\"/>\n| severe_cases    = 19<ref name=\"counter\"/>\n| deaths          = 19<ref name=\"counter\"/>\n| confirmed_cases = 1398<ref name=\"counter\">{{cite web |title=Az\u0259rbaycanda cari v\u0259ziyy\u0259t \u2013 Koronavirus |url=https://koronavirusinfo.az/az\u0259rbaycanda-cari-v\u0259ziyy\u0259t/ |accessdate=19 March 2020 |language=az-AZ}}</ref>\n| total_ili       = \n| website         = [https://koronavirusinfo.az/ Official information portal]<br>{{URL|https://cabmin.gov.az/ |Cabinet of Ministers}}<br>{{URL|http://www.sehiyye.gov.az/ | Ministry of Healthcare}}<br>{{URL|https://its.gov.az/ | State Agency of Mandatory Healt Insurance}}\n}}\nThe [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] was confirmed to have spread to [[Azerbaijan]] when its first case was confirmed in February 2020.\n\n== Background ==\nOn 12 January 2020, the [[World Health Organization]] (WHO) confirmed that a [[novel coronavirus]] was the cause of a respiratory illness in a cluster of people in Wuhan City, Hubei Province, China, which was reported to the WHO on 31 December 2019.<ref name=Elsevier>{{cite web |url=https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center |title=Novel Coronavirus Information Center |last=Elsevier |date= |website=Elsevier Connect|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200130171622/https://www.elsevier.com/connect/coronavirus-information-center|archive-date=30 January 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Reynolds4March2020>{{Cite news |last=Reynolds |first=Matt |url=https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus |title=What is coronavirus and how close is it to becoming a pandemic? |date=4 March 2020 |work=Wired UK|access-date=5 March 2020 |issn=1357-0978|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200305104806/https://www.wired.co.uk/article/china-coronavirus|archive-date=5 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nThe [[Case fatality rate|case fatality ratio]] for COVID-19 has been much lower than [[Severe acute respiratory syndrome|SARS of 2003]],<ref name=Imperial13March2020>{{cite web |url= https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/ |title=Crunching the numbers for coronavirus |website=Imperial News|access-date=15 March 2020|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200319084913/https://www.imperial.ac.uk/news/196137/crunching-numbers-coronavirus/|archive-date=19 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=Gov.ukHCIDDef>{{cite web |url=https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid |title=High consequence infectious diseases (HCID); Guidance and information about high consequence infectious diseases and their management in England |last= |first= |date= |website=GOV.UK |language=en|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200303051938/https://www.gov.uk/guidance/high-consequence-infectious-diseases-hcid|archive-date=3 March 2020|access-date=17 March 2020}}</ref> but the [[Transmission (medicine)|transmission]] has been significantly greater, with a significant total death toll.<ref name=WFSA>{{cite web |url= https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus |title=World Federation Of Societies of Anaesthesiologists \u2013 Coronavirus |last= |first= |date= |website=www.wfsahq.org|url-status=live|archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20200312233527/https://www.wfsahq.org/resources/coronavirus|archive-date=12 March 2020|access-date=15 March 2020}}</ref><ref name=Imperial13March2020/>\n\n== Timeline ==\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/Azerbaijan medical cases chart}}\n\n=== February 2020 ===\n* On 27 February, an operational headquarters under the [[Government of Azerbaijan|Cabinet of Ministers]] was created to prevent danger that the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic|coronavirus pandemic]] could cause, to implement [[Preventive healthcare|prophylactic]] and urgent measures. This headquarters included heads of related state organisations, leading by Azerbaijan's [[Prime Minister of Azerbaijan|Prime Minister]] [[Ali Asadov]] and [[Ministry of Healthcare (Azerbaijan)|Minister of Healthcare]] [[Ogtay Shiraliyev]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cabmin.gov.az/az/article/680/|title=Operational headquarters under Cabinet of Ministers created|last=|first=|date=|website=|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=}}</ref>\n* On 28 February, the country confirmed its first positive case of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]]. The patient, a Russian national, had traveled from [[Iran]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-azerbaijan-idUSKCN20M1IR|title=Azerbaijan reports first case of coronavirus - Ifax|date=2020-02-28|work=Reuters|access-date=2020-02-28|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20200228121136/https://www.reuters.com/article/us-china-health-azerbaijan-idUSKCN20M1IR|archive-date=28 February 2020|language=en}}</ref> Two more cases were later confirmed in the country and they were all isolated. They were Azerbaijani nationals who returned from Iran. On the same day Azerbaijan closed borders with [[Iran]] for 2 weeks.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/02/coronavirus-outbreak-bigger-latest-updates-200228232914773.html|title=COVID-19 cases jump in Iran as Italy toll rises: Live updates &#124; News &#124; al Jazeera}}</ref>\n\n=== March 2020 ===\n* On 2 March, educational processes and other related activities were suspended from 3\u20139 March in all educational institutions across the country to prevent the spread of [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19 infection]], to increase the effectiveness of measures taken in this sphere, and to intensify medical prophylactic, disinfection and other preventive measures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.trend.az/azerbaijan/society/3200643.html|title=Azerbaijan closes down schools, universities due to coronavirus upon Cabinet of Ministers' decision|date=2 March 2020}}</ref> The suspension date was later extended through to 27 March.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nk.gov.az/az/article/702/|title=Az\u0259rbaycan Respublikas\u0131n\u0131n Nazirl\u0259r Kabinetinin yan\u0131nda operativ q\u0259rargah\u0131n M\u018fLUMATI {{!}} Az\u0259rbaycan Respublikas\u0131n\u0131n Nazirl\u0259r Kabineti|date=2020-03-13|website=nk.gov.az|language=az|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n* On 4 March, [[Azerbaijan]] stopped letting trucks and imports coming from Iran to enter the country.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.radiofarda.com/a/azerbaijan-and-iraq-close-borders-to-imports-from-iran/30470820.html|title=Azerbaijan And Iraq Close Borders To Imports From Iran|website=RFE/RL|accessdate=8 March 2020}}</ref>\n* On 5 March, three more people, arriving from the [[Iran|Islamic Republic of Iran]] to Azerbaijan, tested positive for COVID-19. One of them was a [[German citizen]] born in 1988, and two others were Azerbaijani citizens (1994 and 1999) studying in Iran's [[Qom]]. Those people were placed in isolation in a  designated hospital. Operative headquarters under the [[Cabinet of Azerbaijan|Cabinet of Ministers]] said total of 276 people who came from Iran are being kept under quarantine on compulsory condition for 14\u201329 days.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://report.az/en/amp/health/confirmed-coronavirus-cases-reach-six-in-azerbaijan/|title=Confirmed coronavirus cases reach six in Azerbaijan - Report.az}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/azeri/amp/region-51655411|title=Az\u0259rbaycanda daha 3 n\u0259f\u0259rd\u0259 koronavirus a\u015fkarland\u0131|date=27 February 2020|newspaper=BBC News Az\u0259rbaycanca}}</ref>\n* On 7 March, three Azerbaijani citizens, who returned from the Islamic Republic of Iran, were diagnosed with the coronavirus COVID-19. One of them, born in 1938, some time after returning from Iran, went to the hospital due to a health problem. During the examination, he was diagnosed with [[pneumonia]], and laboratory analysis confirmed the fact of infection with coronavirus. Two others, students born in 1993 and 1994, studying in the Iranian city of Qom, were quarantined while crossing the Iran-Azerbaijan border and they had a coronavirus infection.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.trend.az/azerbaijan/3203498.html|title=Three more Azerbaijani citizens test positive for coronavirus after returning from Iran|date=7 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://nk.gov.az/az/article/700/|title=Az\u0259rbaycan Respublikas\u0131 Nazirl\u0259r Kabinetinin yan\u0131nda operativ q\u0259rargah\u0131n M\u018fLUMATI &#124; Az\u0259rbaycan Respublikas\u0131n\u0131n Nazirl\u0259r Kabineti}}</ref>\n* On 9 March, two Azerbaijani citizens (born in 1966 and 1978) who arrived in the country from Iran were infected with the coronavirus COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.trend.az/azerbaijan/society/3204320.html|title=Two more Azerbaijani citizens test positive for coronavirus after returning from Iran|date=2020-03-10|website=Trend.Az|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n* On 10 March, two Azerbaijani citizens (born in 1960 and 1984) tested positive for coronavirus after returning from Iran, Operational Headquarters under the Cabinet of Ministers reported. Three Azerbaijanis, who previously tested positive for coronavirus (born in 1973, 1997 and 1998) recovered after receiving treatment in special hospitals and have already been discharged.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.trend.az/azerbaijan/society/3204964.html|title=Operational Headquarters: Two Azerbaijani citizens test positive for coronavirus after returning from Iran|date=2020-03-10|website=Trend.Az|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref> \n* On 11 March, two more cases have been confirmed. One of them, born in 1969, tested positive for COVID-19 after admitting to hospital for [[chronic kidney disease]] as a complication of [[Systemic lupus erythematosus|SLE]]. She returned from Iran a while ago. The other one was a student born in 1997, who developed fever after returning from [[Italy]]. Both of them put in isolation in special hospital.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.trend.az/azerbaijan/society/3205665.html|title=Operational Headquarters: Two more Azerbaijani citizens who arrived from abroad infected with coronavirus|date=2020-03-11|website=Trend.Az|language=en|access-date=2020-03-13}}</ref>\n* On 12 March, the woman died from [[multiorgan failure]], which diagnosed a day ago with [[Coronavirus disease 2019|COVID-19]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Woman quarantined in Azerbaijan after arriving from Iran died |url=https://en.trend.az/azerbaijan/society/3206349.html |website=Trend.Az |accessdate=13 March 2020 |language=en |date=12 March 2020}}</ref> This marked the first death of coronavirus in Azerbaijan.\n* On 13 March, four more cases have been confirmed. They returned from [[Iran]] and [[Italy]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Operational Headquarters: Four Azerbaijani citizens returning from Iran, Italy infected with coronavirus |url=https://en.trend.az/azerbaijan/society/3206839.html |website=Trend.Az |accessdate=13 March 2020 |language=en |date=13 March 2020}}</ref> Azerbaijan closed borders with\u00a0[[Georgia (country)|Georgia]] for 10 days after phone conversation between [[Ali Asadov|Azerbaijan's Prime Minister Ali Asadov]] with his [[Georgians|Georgian]] counterpart [[Giorgi Gakharia]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.trend.az/azerbaijan/politics/3207164.html|title=Georgian-Azerbaijani border temporarily closed|date=2020-03-13|website=Trend.Az|language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n* On 14 March, three Azerbaijanis, who previously tested positive for coronavirus recovered after receiving treatment in special hospitals and have already been discharged.<ref>{{cite web |title=Az\u0259rbaycan Respublikas\u0131 Nazirl\u0259r Kabinetinin yan\u0131nda operativ q\u0259rargah\u0131n M\u018fLUMATI {{!}} Az\u0259rbaycan Respublikas\u0131n\u0131n Nazirl\u0259r Kabineti |url=https://cabmin.gov.az/az/article/722/ |website=cabmin.gov.az |accessdate=14 March 2020 |language=az |date=14 March 2020}}</ref> Azerbaijan temporarily closed land and air borders with [[Turkey]] mutually after telephone conversation between [[Ilham Aliyev|President of the Republic of Azerbaijan Ilham Aliyev]] and [[Recep Tayyip Erdo\u011fan|President of the Republic of Turkey Recep Tayyip Erdogan]] <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.trend.az/azerbaijan/politics/3207619.html|title=Azerbaijani, Turkish presidents had telephone conversation|date=2020-03-14|website=Trend.Az|language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> The Operational Headquarters under the Azerbaijani Cabinet of Ministers conducted the measures on social isolation that applied countrywide from March 14.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.trend.az/azerbaijan/politics/3207119.html|title=Operational headquarters: Certain measures on social isolation to be applied in Azerbaijan from March 14|date=2020-03-13|website=Trend.Az|language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref> These measures included banning of wedding, mourning ceremonies and other mass gatherings, closure of cultural facilities, theatres, museums, cinemas, entertainment centres, sport centres and other related facilities, prohibition of patient visits by relatives in all medical establishments, specific guidelines  for cafes, restaurants, shops, malls, public transportation and etc.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://news.az/articles/society/146599|title=All wedding gatherings banned in Azerbaijan|website=news.az|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.azernews.az/nation/162929.html|title=Azerbaijan closes number of tourist sites [PHOTO]|date=2020-03-14|website=AzerNews.az|language=en|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cabmin.gov.az/az/article/718/|title=Az\u0259rbaycan Respublikas\u0131 Nazirl\u0259r Kabineti yan\u0131nda operativ q\u0259rargah\u0131n M\u018fLUMATI {{!}} Az\u0259rbaycan Respublikas\u0131n\u0131n Nazirl\u0259r Kabineti|date=2020-03-15|website=cabmin.gov.az|language=az|access-date=2020-03-14}}</ref>\n* On 15 March, four more cases have been confirmed.<ref>{{cite web |title=Az\u0259rbaycan Respublikas\u0131 Nazirl\u0259r Kabinetinin yan\u0131nda operativ q\u0259rargah\u0131n M\u018fLUMATI {{!}} Az\u0259rbaycan Respublikas\u0131n\u0131n Nazirl\u0259r Kabineti |url=https://cabmin.gov.az/az/article/726/ |website=cabmin.gov.az |accessdate=15 March 2020 |language=az |date=15 March 2020}}</ref> Later on the day two more cases confirmed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cabmin.gov.az/az/article/729/|title=Az\u0259rbaycan Respublikas\u0131 Nazirl\u0259r Kabinetinin yan\u0131nda Operativ Q\u0259rargah\u0131n M\u018fLUMATI {{!}} Az\u0259rbaycan Respublikas\u0131n\u0131n Nazirl\u0259r Kabineti|date=2020-03-15|website=cabmin.gov.az|language=az|access-date=2020-03-15}}</ref>\n* On 16 March, mutual visits of Azerbaijani and Russian citizens have been temporarily suspended after telephone conversation took place between Azerbaijan's Prime Minister [[Ali Asadov]] and his [[Prime Minister of Russia|Russian counterpart]] [[Mikhail Mishustin]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.trend.az/azerbaijan/3208723.html|title=Mutual visits of Azerbaijani and Russian citizens temporarily suspended: Operational Headquarters|date=2020-03-16|website=Trend.Az|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> [[Azerbaijan National Academy of Sciences]] reported that work on preparation of vaccines against coronavirus started at Institute of Molecular Biology and Biotechnology.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.trend.az/azerbaijan/3208718.html|title=Azerbaijan to prepare vaccinations against coronavirus|date=2020-03-16|website=Trend.Az|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n* On 17 March, as preventive measures on the spread of coronavirus infection (COVID-19), entry to [[Baku]] and [[Sumqayit|Sumgayit]] cities as well as to [[Absheron District|Absheron]] region was limited.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.trend.az/azerbaijan/society/3209256.html|title=Azerbaijan's Operational Headquarters: Entry to Baku, Sumgayit, Absheron region limited|date=2020-03-17|website=Trend.Az|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> On the same day it was reported that with 9 more cases, total number of cases rose to 34.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.trend.az/azerbaijan/society/3208970.html|title=3 more cases of coronavirus infection detected in Azerbaijan|date=2020-03-17|website=Trend.Az|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.trend.az/azerbaijan/society/3209485.html|title=Six more test positive for coronavirus in Azerbaijan|date=2020-03-17|website=Trend.Az|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n*On 18 March, Operational headquarters reported that  four more patients have been discharged form hospitals after recovering.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.trend.az/azerbaijan/society/3209635.html|title=Four more discharged after recovering from coronavirus in Azerbaijan|date=2020-03-18|website=Trend.Az|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n*On 19 March, [[Ilham Aliyev|Azerbaijan's President Ilham Aliyev]] signed a decree on March 19 on a number of measures to reduce the negative consequences of coronavirus (COVID-19) pandemic and the impact of volatility caused by this infection in the world energy and stock markets on Azerbaijan's economy, macroeconomic stability, employment and business entities in the country. According to the decree, the Cabinet of Ministers was allocated $1 billion [[Azerbaijani manat|manats]] from the state budget to finance the measures.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.trend.az/azerbaijan/politics/3211025.html|title=Azerbaijan's president allocates $1B to Cabinet of Ministers|date=2020-03-19|website=Trend.Az|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> [[President of Azerbaijan|Azerbaijani President]] ordered to establish Support Fund Against Coronavirus. Initially 20 million [[Azerbaijani manat|manats]] allocated from President's Contingency Fund to this fund to enhance effectiveness of fight against coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.trend.az/azerbaijan/politics/3210718.html|title=President Ilham Aliyev: Additional 20 million manats will be allocated from President's Contingency Fund to enhance effectiveness of fight against coronavirus|date=2020-03-19|website=Trend.Az|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.trend.az/azerbaijan/politics/3210761.html|title=Azerbaijani president orders to establish Fund to Support Fund Against Coronavirus|date=2020-03-19|website=Trend.Az|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> It was later reported that President Ilham Aliyev donated his annual salary to this fund.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.trend.az/azerbaijan/politics/3211578.html|title=President Ilham Aliyev donates his annual salary to Fund to Support Fight Against Coronavirus|date=2020-03-21|website=Trend.Az|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>  Later on the day Operational Headquarters under the Cabinet of Ministers reported that ten more people tested positive for coronavirus.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.trend.az/azerbaijan/society/3210735.html|title=Operational Headquarters: 10 more test positive for coronavirus in Azerbaijan|date=2020-03-19|website=Trend.Az|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n*On 20 March, it was reported that a number of government agencies will get a paid leave from March 29 to April 29.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.trend.az/azerbaijan/society/3211370.html|title=A number of government agencies in Azerbaijan to get paid leave for a month|date=2020-03-20|website=Trend.Az|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> Suspension of educational centers further extended through April 19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cabmin.gov.az/az/article/747/|title=Nazirl\u0259r Kabineti yan\u0131nda operativ q\u0259rargah: t\u0259hsil m\u00fc\u0259ssis\u0259l\u0259rind\u0259 t\u0259tilin vaxt\u0131 uzad\u0131ld\u0131 {{!}} Az\u0259rbaycan Respublikas\u0131n\u0131n Nazirl\u0259r Kabineti|date=2020-03-23|website=cabmin.gov.az|language=az|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n*On 21 March, nine more people tested positive.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.trend.az/azerbaijan/society/3211563.html|title=Nine more test positive for coronavirus in Azerbaijan|date=2020-03-21|website=Trend.Az|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> Azerbaijan strict rules and reduction of working hours were applied to cafes, restaurants, tea houses, internet clubs and other public catering services.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.trend.az/azerbaijan/politics/3211575.html|title=Public catering enterprises in Azerbaijan to serve in new mode|date=2020-03-21|website=Trend.Az|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n*On 22 March, twelve more cases, including first human to human transmission inside country was confirmed.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.trend.az/azerbaijan/society/3211787.html|title=Azerbaijan confirms 12 more coronavirus cases|date=2020-03-22|website=Trend.Az|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref> Shopping centers, malls, and other crowded social and cultural facilities closed for a month.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.trend.az/azerbaijan/politics/3211823.html|title=Large shopping centers, malls closed in Azerbaijan: Operational Headquarters|date=2020-03-22|website=Trend.Az|language=en|access-date=2020-03-22}}</ref>\n[[File:Opening of \u201cYeni klinika\u201d medical institution in Baku.jpg|thumb|250px|\u201cYeni klinika\u201d medical institution in Baku opened 28 March 2020 where since the next day COVID-19 infected people with serious symptoms got treatment<ref>[https://president.az/articles/36267 \u0130lham \u018fliyev Bak\u0131da \u201cYeni klinika\u201d tibb m\u00fc\u0259ssis\u0259sinin a\u00e7\u0131l\u0131\u015f\u0131nda i\u015ftirak edib]</ref>]]\n*On 25 March, Chairman of the Azerbaijani Community of [[Nagorno-Karabakh|Nagorno Karabakh]] region of the Republic of Azerbaijan [[Tural Ganjaliyev]] reported that some members of the Armenian Community of [[Nagorno-Karabakh|Nagorno Karabakh]] region of the Republic of Azerbaijan have appealed to him as an elective representative and informed on the increase of the people, infected with severe respiratory disease, pneumania, poor condition of health infrastructure, lack of test kits and medical staff, and expressed their concerns that Armenia and illegal regime hide infection cases of coronavirus (COVID-19) from population.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://ona.az/en/nagorno-karabakh/some-members-of-the-armenian-community-appealed-to-tural-ganjaliyev-infection-cases-of-coronavirus-in-nagorno-garabagh-are-hidden-13395|title=Some members of the Armenian Community appealed to Tural Ganjaliyev: \"Infection cases of coronavirus in Nagorno Garabagh are hidden\"|last=ONA.az|website=ONA|language=az-AZ|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n*On 31 March, Azerbaijan declared nationwide quarantine. People are required to stay in private houses and apartments, permanent or temporary places of residence until 20 April.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.trend.az/azerbaijan/politics/3215334.html|title=Azerbaijan sets additional measures to prevent spread of coronavirus|date=2020-03-30|website=Trend.Az|language=en|access-date=2020-04-01}}</ref>\n\n===April 2020===\n\n* On 2 April, it was reported that in order to obtain permission to leave the place of residence, people must get SMS permissions to go outside for vital services (urgent medical need, to purchase food and other goods or medicines). In order to leave the place of residence in the event of a situation that poses a direct threat to life and health, sending an SMS is not required.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://en.trend.az/azerbaijan/politics/3217188.html|title=Operational Headquarters under Azerbaijani Cabinet of Ministers decides on movement restriction|date=2020-04-02|website=Trend.Az|language=en|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n== Statistics ==\nBelow charts are generated based on daily reports from the website of Ministers Cabinet of Azerbaijan Republic according to the press release of Operational Headquarters under the Cabinet of Ministers on confirmed cases of COVID-19.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cabmin.gov.az//az/|title=Az\u0259rbaycan Respublikas\u0131n\u0131n Nazirl\u0259r Kabineti|date=2020-04-04|website=cabmin.gov.az|language=az|access-date=2020-04-03}}</ref>\n\n{{Graph:Chart\n | width=780\n | height=\n | xAxisTitle=Date of daily report\n | xAxisAngle=-40\n | yAxisTitle=No. of cases\n | legend=Legend\n | y1Title=Confirmed cases\n | y2Title=Active cases\n | y3Title=Recoveries\n | y4Title=Deaths\n | type=line\n | linewidth=1\n | showSymbols=1\n | x=Feb 27,Feb 28,Feb 29,Mar 5,Mar 6,Mar 9,Mar 10,Mar 11,Mar 12,Mar 13,Mar 14,Mar 15,Mar 17,Mar 18,Mar 19,Mar 21,Mar 22,Mar 23,Mar 24,Mar 25,Mar 26,Mar 27,Mar 28,Mar 29,Mar 30,Mar 31,Apr 1,Apr 2,Apr 3,Apr 4,Apr 5,Apr 6,Apr 7,Apr 8,Apr 9,Apr 10, Apr 11, Apr 12, Apr 13, Apr 14, Apr 15, Apr 16, Apr 17, Apr 18, Apr 19\n | y1=0,1,3,6,9,11,13,15,15,19,19,25,34,34,44,53,65,72,87,93,122,165,182,209,273,298,359,400,443,521,584,641,717,822,926,991,1058,1098,1148,1197,1253,1283,