ing people]]\n[[Category:Kannada film editors]]\n[[Category:Film editors from Karnataka]]\n", "name_user": "Woodlot", "label": "safe", "comment": "spelling", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Srikanth_Gowda"}
{"title_page": "Department of War Studies, King's College London", "text_new": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name              = Department of War Studies, <br /> King's College London\n| parent            = Faculty of Social Science & Public Policy, [[King's College London]]\n| image_name        = File:KCL King's Building 3 Final.jpg\n| image_size        = 310px\n| logo                  = KCL War Studies logo.jpeg\n| logo_size         = 150px\n| caption           = \n| established       = 1962\n| academic_affiliation = \n| head_label        = Head of Department\n| head              = Michael Goodman\n| academic_staff    = 100\n| students          = 1,000\n| location          = [[Strand, London|Strand]], London\n| postgrad          =\n| website           = [http://www.kcl.ac.uk/warstudies/ kcl.ac.uk/warstudies]\n}}\nThe '''Department of War Studies (DWS)''' is an academic department in the School of Security Studies within the Faculty of Social Science & Public Policy at [[King's College London]] in London, United Kingdom. Along with other politics and international studies units at King's College London, it ranks amongst the top places for [[international relations]] in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/university-subject-rankings/2013/politics |title=QS World University Rankings by Subject 2013 \u2013 Politics & International Studies |publisher=topuniversities.com |accessdate=17 January 2014}}</ref> The department is devoted to the multi-disciplinary study of war and diplomacy within the broad remit of [[international relations]].\n\nThe department's alumni includes senior government officials, military personnel, diplomats, journalists, academics and businesspeople. Amongst them are former Prime Minister of Jordan [[Marouf al-Bakhit]]; Special Representative of the UN Secretary-General for Iraq [[Nickolay Mladenov]] and former Commandant General Royal Marines [[Robert Fry|Sir Robert Fry]].  The department is affiliated with numerous think-tanks and foreign policy institutions.<ref>[http://www.kcl.ac.uk/schools/sspp/ws/about/ King's College London \u2013 School of Social Science & Public Policy]. Kcl.ac.uk (19 June 2013). Retrieved 20 July 2013.</ref> It also houses numerous research institutes and centres, including the [[Liddell Hart Centre for Military Archives]].\n\nSince 2019, the Head of Department has been Michael Goodman. The Department of War Studies is located on the 6th floor of the King's Building on the [[Strand Campus]] of King's College London.\n\n== History ==\nA Department of Military Science existed at King's College London from 1848 to 1859. Military Science was subsequently approved as a subject for the Bachelor of Arts and Bachelor of Science general degrees from 1913, and was taught under the Faculty of Arts and also the Faculty of Engineering.\n\nIn 1926 the intervention of William Norton Medlicott prevented the Department of History from ridding itself of the lectureship in Military History.<ref>http://www.oxforddnb.com/templates/article.jsp?articleid=66374&back=</ref> With [[War Office]] support the Military Studies Department was established in 1926 and formed part of the Faculty of Arts, with Major General [[Frederick Barton Maurice|Sir Frederick Barton Maurice]] holding the Chair. It became known as the War Studies Department in 1943 but was discontinued in 1948, although the subject continued to be taught under the Department of Medieval and Modern History.\n\nFollowing the [[World War II]], there was an initiative by senior members of [[University of London]] notably [[Lionel Robbins, Baron Robbins|Lionel Robbins]], [[Charles Webster (historian)|Sir Charles Webster]] and [[Sir (William) Keith Hancock|Keith Hancock]], to revive Military Studies at the University. In 1953, [[Michael Howard (historian)|Sir Michael Howard]] was appointed to the Lectureship in Military Studies, and by 1962 Sir Michael was able to reinstate the Department of War Studies to offer postgraduate courses.\n\nA Bachelor of Arts degree in War Studies was offered from 1992 onwards. The department became part of the School of Humanities in 1989 and the School of Social Science and Public Policy in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kingscollections.org/catalogues/kclca/collection/k/10ki4655 |title=King's College London: Department of War Studies Records |publisher=King's Collections |accessdate=17 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140121043821/http://www.kingscollections.org/catalogues/kclca/collection/k/10ki4655 |archivedate=21 January 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012 the department celebrated its 50th anniversary, with a series of celebratory events to mark the occasion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kcl.ac.uk/newsevents/news/newsrecords/2012/01Jan/War-Studies-celebrates-50-years.aspx |title=  War Studies celebrates 50 years|publisher=King's College London |accessdate=18 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Notable alumni and students==\n{{See also|List of King's College London alumni|}}\n\n[[File:Maroufalbakhit.jpg|thumb|right|Prime Minister of Jordan [[Marouf al-Bakhit]]|155px]]\n[[File:Nataliagherman.jpg|thumb|right|Prime Minister of Moldova [[Natalia Gherman]]|155px]]\n[[File:Argentina- John Freeman (8473848056).jpg|thumb|right|Governor of the Turks and Caicos Islands [[John Freeman (diplomat)|John Freeman]]|155px]]\n[[File:Siradrianbradshaw.jpg|thumb|Deputy Supreme Allied Commander Europe [[Adrian Bradshaw|Sir Adrian Bradshaw]]|155px]] \n[[File:Sir Robert Fry - Self Portrait.jpg|thumb|right|Commandant General Royal Marines [[Robert Fry|Sir Robert Fry]]|155px]]\n[[File:Stuart Skeates.jpg|thumb|Commandant of RMA Sandhurst [[Stuart Skeates]]|155px]]\n\n===Government and politics===\n*[[Marouf al-Bakhit]] (PhD 1990), former Prime Minister of Jordan<ref name=\"Biography of Marouf al-Bakhit\">{{cite web|url=http://www.globalinsight.com/Perspective/PerspectiveDetail2538.htm|title=Biography of Marouf al-Bakhit|accessdate=22 December 2008}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n*[[Martin Bourke]] (MA 1970), former Governor of the Turks and Caicos Islands<ref name=\"Martin Bourke\">{{cite web|url=http://www.ukwhoswho.com/view/article/oupww/whoswho/U8222|title=Martin Bourke|publisher=[[Who's Who (UK)|Who's Who]]}}{{subscription required}}</ref>\n*[[Tan Chuan-Jin]] (MA 1999), Speaker of the Parliament of Singapore\n*[[Kayode Fayemi]] (PhD 1987), Nigeria's Minister of Solid Minerals Development\n*[[Mark Francois]] (MA 1987), Conservative Member of UK Parliament\n*[[Christopher Geidt|Sir Christopher Geidt]] (MA 1987), former [[Private Secretary to the Sovereign]] (Queen Elizabeth II)\n*[[Natalia Gherman]] (MA 1999), former Deputy Prime Minister of Moldova\n*[[John Hillen]] (MA 1993), former US Assistant Secretary of State for Political-Military Affairs\n*[[Dan Jarvis]] (MA 2011), Labour Member of UK Parliament\n*[[Nickolay Mladenov]] (MA 1996), UN Special Coordinator for the Middle East Peace Process\n*[[Ji\u0159\u00ed \u0160ediv\u00fd]] (MA 1994), Permanent Representative of the Czech Republic to NATO\n*[[Keith Simpson (politician)|Keith Simpson]] (postgraduate research 1972), Conservative Member of Parliament\n*[[Pritam Singh (Singaporean politician)|Pritam Singh]] (MA 2004), Singaporean Member of Parliament\n*[[Shaun Spiers]] (MA 1985), former Labour Member of the European Parliament\n*[[Eleni Stavrou]] (MA; PhD), Member of the Cyprus House of Representatives\n\n===Military, security and diplomacy===\n*[[A.T.M. Zahirul Alam]] (MA 1993), former Force Commander of [[United Nations Mission in Liberia]]\n*[[Adrian Bradshaw|Sir Adrian Bradshaw]] (MA 2005), former [[Deputy Supreme Allied Commander Europe]] and former UK Commander of Land Forces\n*[[Paul Crespo]] (MA 1990), former US Marine captain, risk analyst and activist\n*[[Peter Drissell]] (MA 1994), former [[Commandant-General of the RAF Regiment]]\n*[[Richard A. Falkenrath]] (PhD 1993), former Deputy Commissioner for Counterterrorism at [[NYPD]]\n*[[John Freeman (diplomat)|John Freeman]] (PhD 1984) [[Governor of the Turks and Caicos Islands]]\n*[[Robert Fry|Sir Robert Fry]] (MA 1987), former [[Commandant General Royal Marines]]\n*[[Wira Gardiner|Sir Wira Gardiner]] (MA 1980), New Zealander public servant\n*[[Judith Gough]] (MA 2012), British Ambassador to Ukraine\n*[[Syed Ata Hasnain]] (MA 2006), former Military Secretary of the Indian Army\n*[[Md Hashim bin Hussein]] (MA 1991), former Chief of the Malaysian Army\n*[[Ola Ibrahim]] (MA 2002),  former Chief of the Defence Staff of the Nigerian Armed Forces\n*[[Simon Mayall|Sir Simon Mayall]] (MA 2003), former British Deputy Chief of the Defence Staff\n*[[Hugh Mortimer]] (MA 1973), former British Ambassador to Slovenia\n*[[Tim Radford (British Army officer)|Tim Radford]] (MA), British Commander Allied Rapid Reaction Corps \n*[[Maroof Raza]] (MA), Indian strategic affairs analyst\n*[[Ayesha Siddiqa]] (PhD 1996), Pakistani military scientist\n*[[Stuart Skeates]] (MA 1999), British Standing Joint Force Commander\n*[[Frank A. Rose]] (MA 1999), US Assistant Secretary of State for Arms Control, Verification, and Compliance<ref>[https://2009-2017.state.gov/r/pa/ei/biog/bureau/131258.htm United States Department of State]</ref>\n\n===Academia, media and business===\n*[[Ali Ansari]] (MA 1990), Professor of History at the University of St Andrews\n*[[Ruaridh Arrow]] (BA 2001), Senior producer BBC Newsnight, writer and film-maker\n*[[Abdul Razak Baginda]], (MA 1984), Malaysian political analyst\n*[[Brian Bond]] (MA 1962), Military historian\n*[[Ahron Bregman]] (PhD 1994), British-Israeli political scientist\n*[[Paula Broadwell]] (PhD Student), biographer of General David Petraeus\n*[[Matthew Bryden]] (PhD Student), Canadian political activist\n*[[Gwynne Dyer]] (PhD 1973), journalist\n*[[Andrew Exum]] (PhD 2010), Middle East Scholar\n*[[Daniel Ford]] (MA 2010), author\n*[[Ian Gooderson]] (MA PhD), Naval historian\n*[[Andrew Gordon (naval historian)|Andrew Gordon]] (PhD 1983), Naval historian\n*[[Eric Grove]] (MA 1971), British Naval historian\n*[[Rosemary Hollis]] (MA 1975) British political scientist\n*[[Sam Instone]] (BA 1998), Founder and current Chief Executive of AES International\n*[[Andrew Lambert]] (MA PhD), Military historian\n*[[Michael A. Levi]] (PhD 2006), CFR Senior Fellow\n*[[Sophie Long]] (BA 1997), BBC News presenter\n*[[Peter R. Neumann]] (PhD 2002), Terrorism expert\n*[[Peter Paret]] (PhD 1960), Military historian\n*[[Tom Rogan]] (BA 2008), journalist\n*[[Philip Sabin]] (PhD 1984), Military historian\n*[[Yezid Sayigh]] (PhD 1987), Middle East scholar\n*[[Gary Sheffield (historian)|Gary Sheffield]] (PhD 1994), Military historian\n*[[David Stahel]] (MA 2000), historian\n*[[Nicholas Stuart]] (MA 1984), journalist\n*[[Geoffrey Till]] (PhD 1976), Maritime historian\n*[[Alexander Windsor, Earl of Ulster]] (BA 1996), Director of Transnational Crisis Project\n*[[Kieran West]] (MA 2005), Olympic champion rower\n*[[Colin White (historian)|Colin White]] (MA 1975), former Director of the Royal Naval Museum\n\n== Past and present faculty ==\n{| class=\"wikitable floatright\"\n|+ Heads of Department\n! Period\n! Head\n|-\n|1962\u20131968\n|[[Michael Howard (historian)|Sir Michael Howard]]\n|-\n|1968\u20131978\n|[[Laurence Martin|Sir Laurence Martin]] \n|-\n|1978\u20131982\n|Wolf Mendl\n|-\n|1982\u20131997\n|[[Lawrence Freedman|Sir Lawrence Freedman]]\n|-\n|1997\u20132001\n|Christopher Dandeker\n|-\n|2001\u20132007\n|Brian Holden-Reid\n|-\n|2007\u20132013\n|Mervyn Frost\n|-\n|2013\u20132016\n|Theo Farrell\n|-\n|2016\u20132019\n|Michael Rainsborough\n|-\n|2019\u2013present\n|Michael Goodman\n|}\n\n{{Div col|colwidth=20em}}\n*[[James M. Acton]]\n*[[Robert J. Art]]\n*[[Mats Berdal]]\n*[[Didier Bigo]]\n*[[Philip Bobbitt]]\n*[[Brian Bond]]\n*[[Ahron Bregman]]\n*[[Bill Durodi\u00e9]]\n*[[Nicholas Eftimiades]]\n*[[Joel Hayward]]\n*[[Michael Howard (historian)|Michael Howard]]\n*[[Vivienne Jabri]]\n*[[Ashley Jackson (historian)|Ashley Jackson]]\n*[[Stephen Jolly (academic)|Stephen Jolly]]\n*[[Mark Laity]]\n*[[Andrew Lambert]]\n*[[Lawrence Freedman]]\n*[[Thomas Gomart]]\n*[[Barry M. Gough]]\n*[[Beatrice Heuser]]\n*[[Richard Ned Lebow]]\n*[[Anatol Lieven]]\n*[[Colin J. McInnes]]\n*[[Anand Menon]]\n*[[John Nagl]]\n*[[Peter R. Neumann]]\n*[[David Omand]]\n*[[Richard Overy]]\n*[[Friedbert Pfl\u00fcger]]\n*[[Jonathon Riley (British Army officer)|Jonathon Riley]]\n*[[Andrew Roberts (historian)|Andrew Roberts]]\n*[[Philip Sabin]]\n*[[John Sawers]]\n*[[Yezid Sayigh]]\n*[[Nigel Sheinwald]]\n*[[Jack Spence (academic)|Jack Spence]]\n*[[Julian Thompson (Royal Marines officer)|Julian Thompson]]\n*[[Cedric Thornberry]]\n*[[Guglielmo Verdirame]]\n*[[Kenneth Waltz]]\n*[[Simon Wessely]]\n*[[Ken Young]]\n*[[Peter Zimmerman]]\n{{Div col end}}\n\n== Tolstoy Cup ==\n{{Main|Tolstoy Cup}}\n\nThe Tolstoy Cup is an annual [[association football|football]] match played between the students of the Department of War Studies at King's and the Department of [[Peace and Conflict Studies|Peace Studies]] at the [[University of Bradford]] since 1995. The rivalry between 'Peace Studies' and 'War Studies' was featured on the ''[[Financial Times]]'' list of \"Great college sports rivalries\".<ref name=ft>{{cite news|url=http://www.ft.com/cms/s/2/66e2c658-5664-11e0-84e9-00144feab49a.html|title=The List: Five great college sports rivalries|first=Izabella|last=Scott|date=25 March 2011|newspaper=Financial Times|location=London}}</ref> The competition is named after ''[[War and Peace]]'', the 1869 novel written by the Russian author [[Leo Tolstoy]]. The \"trophy\" is a framed copy of the book. It is kept by the department of the current winners.\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|2}}\n\n==External links==\n\n{{Portal|London|War}}\n* [http://www.kcl.ac.uk/sspp/departments/warstudies/index.aspx Official website of the Department of War Studies]\n\n{{King's College London}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Department Of War Studies, KCL}}\n[[Category:Departments of King's College London]]\n[[Category:Military education and training in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:1962 establishments in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:Schools of international relations]]\n", "text_old": "{{EngvarB|date=October 2017}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2017}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name              = Department of War Studies, <br /> King's College London\n| parent            = Faculty of Social Science & Public Policy, [[King's College London]]\n| image_name        = File:KCL King's Building 3 Final.jpg\n| image_size        = 310px\n| logo                  = KCL War Studies logo.jpeg\n| logo_size         = 150px\n| caption           = \n| established       = 1962\n| academic_affiliation = \n| head_label        = Head of Department\n| head              = Michael Goodman\n| academic_staff    = 100\n| students          = 1,000\n| location          = [[Strand, London|Strand]], London\n| postgrad          =\n| website           = [http://www.kcl.ac.uk/warstudies/ kcl.ac.uk/warstudies]\n}}\nThe '''Department of War Studies (DWS)''' is an academic department in the School of Security Studies within the Faculty of Social Science & Public Policy at [[King's College London]] in London, United Kingdom. Along with other politics and international studies units at King's College London, it ranks amongst the top places for [[international relations]] in the world.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.topuniversities.com/university-rankings/university-subject-rankings/2013/politics |title=QS World University Rankings by Subject 2013 \u2013 Politics & International Studies |publisher=topuniversities.com |accessdate=17 January 2014}}</ref> The department is devoted to the multi-disciplinary study of war and diplomacy within the broad remit of [[international relations]].\n\nThe department's alumni includes senior government officials, military personnel, diplomats, journalists, academics and businesspeople. Amongst them are former Prime Minister of Jordan [[Marouf al-Bakhit]]; Special Representative of the UN Secretary-General for Iraq [[Nickolay Mladenov]] and former Commandant General Royal Marines [[Robert Fry|Sir Robert Fry]].  The department is affiliated with numerous think-tanks and foreign policy institutions.<ref>[http://www.kcl.ac.uk/schools/sspp/ws/about/ King's College London \u2013 School of Social Science & Public Policy]. Kcl.ac.uk (19 June 2013). Retrieved 20 July 2013.</ref> It also houses numerous research institutes and centres, including the [[Liddell Hart Centre for Military Archives]].\n\nSince 2019, the Head of Department has been Michael Goodman. The Department of War Studies is located on the 6th floor of the King's Building on the [[Strand Campus]] of King's College London.\n\n== History ==\nA Department of Military Science existed at King's College London from 1848 to 1859. Military Science was subsequently approved as a subject for the Bachelor of Arts and Bachelor of Science general degrees from 1913, and was taught under the Faculty of Arts and also the Faculty of Engineering.\n\nIn 1926 the intervention of William Norton Medlicott prevented the Department of History from ridding itself of the lectureship in Military History.<ref>http://www.oxforddnb.com/templates/article.jsp?articleid=66374&back=</ref> With [[War Office]] support the Military Studies Department was established in 1926 and formed part of the Faculty of Arts, with Major General [[Frederick Barton Maurice|Sir Frederick Barton Maurice]] holding the Chair. It became known as the War Studies Department in 1943 but was discontinued in 1948, although the subject continued to be taught under the Department of Medieval and Modern History.\n\nFollowing the [[World War II]], there was an initiative by senior members of [[University of London]] notably [[Lionel Robbins, Baron Robbins|Lionel Robbins]], [[Charles Webster (historian)|Sir Charles Webster]] and [[Sir (William) Keith Hancock|Keith Hancock]], to revive Military Studies at the University. In 1953, [[Michael Howard (historian)|Sir Michael Howard]] was appointed to the Lectureship in Military Studies, and by 1962 Sir Michael was able to reinstate the Department of War Studies to offer postgraduate courses.\n\nA Bachelor of Arts degree in War Studies was offered from 1992 onwards. The department became part of the School of Humanities in 1989 and the School of Social Science and Public Policy in 2001.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kingscollections.org/catalogues/kclca/collection/k/10ki4655 |title=King's College London: Department of War Studies Records |publisher=King's Collections |accessdate=17 January 2014 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20140121043821/http://www.kingscollections.org/catalogues/kclca/collection/k/10ki4655 |archivedate=21 January 2014 }}</ref>\n\nIn 2012 the department celebrated its 50th anniversary, with a series of celebratory events to mark the occasion.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.kcl.ac.uk/newsevents/news/newsrecords/2012/01Jan/War-Studies-celebrates-50-years.aspx |title=  War Studies celebrates 50 years|publisher=King's College London |accessdate=18 January 2014}}</ref>\n\n== Notable alumni and students==\n{{See also|List of King's College London alumni|}}\n\n[[File:Maroufalbakhit.jpg|thumb|right|Prime Minister of Jordan [[Marouf al-Bakhit]]|155px]]\n[[File:Nataliagherman.jpg|thumb|right|Prime Minister of Moldova [[Natalia Gherman]]|155px]]\n[[File:Argentina- John Freeman (8473848056).jpg|thumb|right|Governor of the Turks and Caicos Islands [[John Freeman (diplomat)|John Freeman]]|155px]]\n[[File:Siradrianbradshaw.jpg|thumb|Deputy Supreme Allied Commander Europe [[Adrian Bradshaw|Sir Adrian Bradshaw]]|155px]] \n[[File:Sir Robert Fry - Self Portrait.jpg|thumb|right|Commandant General Royal Marines [[Robert Fry|Sir Robert Fry]]|155px]]\n[[File:Stuart Skeates.jpg|thumb|Commandant of RMA Sandhurst [[Stuart Skeates]]|155px]]\n\n